The first round of hearings is over. More than a dozen closed-door depositions are out in the open. The impeachment inquiry is headed into its next phase.
After weeks of laying out their evidence, Democrats will now decide which potential charges to level against against President Trump. Unless additional public testimony is scheduled, that means the center of gravity in the impeachment process will soon shift to the House Judiciary Committee, which is holding its first hearing on impeachment on Wednesday. That committee is expected to draft articles of impeachment based on a forthcoming report from the House Intelligence Committee.
At various points, Democrats have said that they already have the â€œsmoking gunâ€ evidence needed to convince the public that Trumpâ€™s conduct was serious enough to warrant his removal from office. And throughout the impeachment process, Democrats have laid out a detailed timeline they say implicates Trump and his allies in a scheme to pressure Ukraine to pursue investigations of the presidentâ€™s political rival. But while the House seems likely to vote on impeachment, the impact of the case against Trump may ultimately depend on what the American public â€” not the House Democrats â€” regards as the â€œsmoking guns.â€ As we await the release of the Democratsâ€™ report and the next round of hearings, itâ€™s a good moment to take stock of the â€œsmoking gunsâ€ they have â€” and donâ€™t have.
There is, at present, no single piece of evidence that conclusively links Trump to the Ukraine scandal like the tape transcript of President Nixon ordering the Watergate cover-up. That particular piece of evidence was such a decisive â€œsmoking gunâ€ that its release forced Nixonâ€™s resignation within a matter of days. Democratsâ€™ case against Trump, on the other hand, doesnâ€™t have that one key piece of evidence directly linking Trump to a quid pro quo. So a question moving forward is whether Democrats have enough of a â€œsmoking gunâ€ to persuade voters that Trump committed impeachable offenses â€” or if the missing evidence will turn out to be a lifeline for Trump.
In broad strokes, Democrats laid out three questions at the beginning of the public phase of the inquiry, which they said would serve as the foundation for their investigation (and perhaps also the articles of impeachment). Those questions are:
Democratsâ€™ evidence for the first question â€” that he asked a foreign leader for an investigation of his political rival â€” is particularly strong. They donâ€™t just have a single smoking gun regarding whether Trump or the people close to him asked the Ukrainian president and other high-level officials to open an investigation into the Bidens â€” they have a whole smoldering arsenal.
Particularly key is the summary of the July 25 call between Trump and Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelensky, which was actually released before Democrats even began interviewing witnesses. (The White House released the summary a month after a whistleblower filed a complaint about the call.) In the now-infamous conversation, Trump asked Zelensky to â€œdo us a favorâ€ and open investigations into 2016 election interference and the Bidens. While Trump has denied that he did anything wrong on the call, that summary is proof that Trump mentioned investigations to Zelensky, and makes it pretty hard to argue that Trump didnâ€™t want Ukraine to open them.
Thatâ€™s important because over the course of the public testimony, the Democrats have also tried to establish that this wasnâ€™t just a one-off request. According to Gordon Sondland, the American ambassador to the European Union and an integral figure in pushing for the investigations, he and others were just following the presidentâ€™s orders, something which he testified that Trump had made clear on several different occasions. That testimony was underscored by an account from a second witness, diplomat David Holmes, who said he overheard a call between Sondland and Trump on July 26, where Trump reportedly asked Sondland about whether Zelensky was going to commit to the investigations. Sondland disputed a few of Holmesâ€™s details in his testimony, like whether he mentioned the name â€œBiden.â€ But he largely agreed with the substance of what Holmes said, adding to the Democratsâ€™ evidence that Trump himself was asking about investigations.
Whether Democrats have a smoking gun for their third question â€” if there was an effort to cover up or suppress information about Trumpâ€™s actions on Ukraine â€” is more debatable. They donâ€™t, for example, have much evidence from the hearings of an internal effort to cover up the July 25 call. Several witnesses were questioned about why the July 25 call record was moved onto a secure server, or why a few words and phrases seemed to be missing from the call summary. But none of them were willing to say they saw a concerted effort to conceal information.
An obstruction charge is still on the table, though, as Democrats have indicated they could instead draft a narrower article of impeachment around obstruction or contempt of Congress, focusing on the White Houseâ€™s blanket refusal to cooperate with the inquiry. Democrats like Rep. Adam Schiff, the chairman of the House Intelligence Committee, have already said that this is an impeachable offense. Whether the public will agree remains to be seen, since this has been the Trump administrationâ€™s attitude toward all congressional investigations since Democrats took control of the House.
But of course, the Democrats are still missing perhaps the most essential piece of the puzzle â€” a smoking gun for their second question of whether Trump ordered that military aid and/or a White House meeting be conditioned on the investigations.
To be sure, Democrats do have a wide array of evidence strongly suggesting that the people involved in pushing for the investigations â€” including the Ukrainians â€” understood that a White House meeting and nearly $400 million in military aid hung in the balance. Multiple witnesses testified over the course of the public hearings that it was clear to them that there was a quid pro quo. But as Republicans pointed out repeatedly over the course of the hearings, none of these witnesses ever talked to Trump directly. Even Sondland, the one witness who did communicate with Trump directly about the investigations, said he only â€œpresumedâ€ there was a connection and had never heard Trump say it.
There are other witnesses who could help fill in the blanks. Acting White House chief of staff Mick Mulvaney, who witnesses say delivered Trumpâ€™s order to freeze the aid, seems like heâ€™s in a position to shed light on at least some of this mystery. And Rudy Giuliani, the presidentâ€™s personal lawyer, would also presumably be able to offer crucial input about his involvement in the pressure campaign, too â€” since witness after witness described him as the person tasked with carrying out Trumpâ€™s orders. Of course, the rub is neither seems likely to comply with the Democratsâ€™ subpoena to testify, so Democrats have said theyâ€™ll press ahead with the impeachment process rather than try to force Mulvaney and others to testify through what would almost certainly be a lengthy court battle. Democrats did score a win in court last week in case involving another recalcitrant witness, former White House counsel Don McGahn, when a judge ruled that White House officials canâ€™t ignore congressional subpoenas â€” but that ruling is under appeal, and itâ€™s not clear how it would affect other impeachment witnesses.
Itâ€™s possible, too, that this particular â€œsmoking gunâ€ â€” that is, direct evidence that Trump ordered a quid pro quo â€” might not exist. It could be that Trump truly didnâ€™t make the connection or as Trumpâ€™s former personal lawyer, Michael Cohen, testified earlier this year, it could because Trump frequently speaks in â€œcode,â€ rather than giving direct orders. That doesnâ€™t mean that the connection between the investigations, the aid, and the White House meeting wasnâ€™t apparent to everyone involved. But it does potentially deprive Democrats of a smoking gun as dramatic and decisive as the tape that ended Nixonâ€™s presidency. Over the next few weeks, weâ€™ll see just how much of a barrier that turns out to be.\n|end|\n
