The California presidential primary on March 3 wonâ€™t be the only hotly contested race on the Golden State ballot: There will also be a special election in Californiaâ€™s 25th District.
Freshman Democratic Rep. Katie Hill resigned her seat in early November amid allegations of improper relations with her staff. Democrats now face a precursor to 2020 as the party gauges its strength in one of its new suburban pickups. Hill won the Los Angeles metropolitan-area seat by about 9 points in 2018â€™s blue wave, but FiveThirtyEightâ€™s partisan lean metric1 indicates that the seat doesnâ€™t lean toward either party, which means Democrats donâ€™t have a built-in advantage. And with former Republican Rep. Steve Knight back on the ballot, itâ€™s likely to once again be a competitive contest.
Suburban areas like those in Californiaâ€™s 25th District played a pivotal role in Democratsâ€™ takeover of the House in 2018 and will be crucial in 2020, too. In fact, based on CityLabâ€™s congressional district density categorizations, which range from â€œPure Ruralâ€ to â€œPure Urban,â€ 70 percent of Democratic House pickups last year came from the two mostly suburban categories, â€œSparse Suburbanâ€ and â€œDense Suburban.â€ Democrats have continued to make gains in 2019, but what happens in the California 25th â€” considered â€œDense Suburbanâ€ â€” will be important in helping us assess Democratsâ€™ newfound suburban strength.
