According to our poll with Ipsos, a majority of Americans agree that all three of these things happened and that theyâ€™re inappropriate behaviors for a president. But thereâ€™s less consensus about whether theyâ€™re impeachable offenses. Republicans, in particular, seem unconvinced that any of the three prongs in Democratsâ€™ case against Trump are impeachable offenses.
Share of respondents in a FiveThirtyEight/Ipsos poll who believe Trump took certain actions relating to Ukraine and whether, if they did happen, those actions would be impeachable or inappropriate
From a poll with 2,088 respondents, conducted from Nov. 13 to Nov. 18
But the differences in these responses suggests that while the public mostly views Trumpâ€™s conduct as serious, it might still be difficult for Democrats to build a broad public consensus around their articles of impeachment. As the table above shows, respondents were more likely to agree that Trump asked Ukraine to investigate the Bidens than to believe that Trump held up security aid over the investigations, or tried to cover up his actions. That makes sense â€” the White Houseâ€™s own summary of Trumpâ€™s July call with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky seems to confirm as much. But while most thought all three of those actions would be inappropriate, a bare majority (51 percent) said that Trump asking Ukraineâ€™s government to investigate the Bidens would not be an impeachable offense.
This pattern is especially noticeable among Republicans. They agree, for the most part, that Trump did ask Ukraine to investigate the Bidens. But they mostly donâ€™t think itâ€™s inappropriate or impeachable for Trump to have done so. And while majorities of Republicans think that it would be inappropriate for Trump to have withheld military aid over the investigations or tried to hide information from Congress, they are much less convinced that either of those things actually happened.
This could change as the televised hearings wrap up, but right now, the proceedings are getting a lot of attention. Over half (57 percent) of Americans in our survey said theyâ€™re following the impeachment proceedings somewhat or very closely, with Democrats a bit more likely to say theyâ€™re following closely.
The problem for Democrats is that the people who havenâ€™t fully made up their minds about impeachment â€” regardless of their political orientation â€” donâ€™t seem to be very engaged with the process. Only about 34 percent of respondents who arenâ€™t as certain about their stance on impeachment are following the process somewhat or very closely, compared to 66 percent of respondents who are more certain. So while there are people out there who could still be convinced by the Democratsâ€™ case against Trump, theyâ€™re also less likely to be paying attention.
Methodology: All the data presented here come from polling done by Ipsos for FiveThirtyEight, using Ipsosâ€™s KnowledgePanel, a probability-based online panel that is recruited to be representative of the U.S. population. For this study, the same group of respondents is contacted for an interview six times â€” roughly every two weeks for three months â€” to track whether and how their answers changed; this is the initial wave of this panel survey, conducted from Nov. 13 to Nov. 18 among a general population sample of adults with an oversample of independents, garnering 2,088 respondents. The study weighting included an adjustment for party identification so that results reflect the general population of U.S. adults. The poll has a margin of error of +/- 2.4 percentage points.\n|end|\n
