It would be fair to say that Pete Buttigieg is experiencing something of a moment. Again.
Earlier this year, he splashed down into Americaâ€™s consciousness as the young, gay, veteran mayor of South Bend, Indiana, who wanted to be president and would definitely appear on your podcast or morning show. His press coverage was so ubiquitous that it merited a profile of the person arranging it, his communications director, Lis Smith, and helped get him a bump in the polls and fundraising. But the Democratic primary race got crowded and others had their moments, too. Buttigieg faded somewhat â€” he fell from an 8.4 percent peak in the Real Clear Politics national average and settled into the 4 to 6 percent range. He was a nice young man who always looked dressed for a wedding dance floor â€” suit pants, shirt and tie, but rarely a jacket â€” who would perhaps have his shot somewhere down the line, but not now.
That changed this fall. Buttigieg has surged back into the conversation about who the top tier of candidates really are. (He recently said he thought the race was getting down to a two-way one between himself and Sen. Elizabeth Warren.) That confidence â€” or overconfidence, depending on who youâ€™re talking to â€” has to do in large part with his performance in Iowa polls and in the money race. The most recent Monmouth University poll of the state shows him leading the race at 22 percent. Buttigieg raised more money than Joe Biden, the leader in national polls, according to third-quarter fundraising reports, trailing only Sen. Bernie Sanders and Warren in the cash grab.
Which is why I found myself on a curb in Manchester, New Hampshire, on a recent morning, waiting for the Buttigieg campaign bus to arrive. When it pulled up in all its tricked-out Trailways glory, it was promptly loaded with the suitcases of a couple dozen journalists, who then headed into the Rex Theatre, where a moderate-sized crowd of New Englanders waited. The Veterans Day weekend bus tour junket had begun.
Inside, country music and Lizzo played while people milled about, dutifully sporting all manner of â€œPeteâ€ gear. The campaignâ€™s main colors are blue and gold, same as his hometown University of Notre Dame. But according to the campaignâ€™s official â€œcolor story,â€ the gold is actually â€œHeartland Yellowâ€ and there are all manner of blues, including one called â€œCalm Blueâ€ that appears next to a picture of Buttigieg himself. The page notes, â€œPete Buttigieg is unapologetically substantive yet salt-of-the-earth.â€ A more succinct rendering of the Buttigieg campaign ethos you could not find.
Many of the voters at the morning event were older and seemed interested in what they saw as Buttigiegâ€™s potentially broad appeal. Janice Williamson, 67, of Wakefield, Massachusetts, and Diane Gaucher, â€œolder than she is,â€ of Manchester, said they were Buttigieg-curious in large part because of his seeming strategic advantage in the race â€” his â€œelectability,â€ to use the language of punditry.
â€œI feel heâ€™s well positioned,â€ Gaucher said. â€œThe country is ready for a more gentle approach.â€ Williamson said she liked Biden, but felt he was too old. As for Warren? â€œWhen I hear her talk, I want to slap her, even if I agree with her,â€ she said.
As voters have developed Goldilocks syndrome about the leading Democratic candidates â€” too old, too liberal, too â€¦ female? â€” Buttigieg has benefitted from the strong vanilla flavor of his political porridge. His stump speech is about â€œAmerican values, correctly understood,â€ addresses â€œthe crisis of belonging,â€ scolds the â€œcheap nationalism of hugging the flagâ€ and encourages â€œRepublicans of conscienceâ€ to come on into the Democratic Party.
Joe Raedle / Getty Images
Like Biden, Buttigieg is selling voters on a nostalgic return to some age of innocence and patriotism that existed before Trump. The next target is New Hampshire, where heâ€™s mostly been trailing Biden, Warren and Sanders in polls. The Buttigieg team is betting that the momentum of good performances in these two early states will leapfrog their candidate into the broader Democratic primary voter consciousness â€” think California and other Super Tuesday states.
But while fundraising is healthy and Iowa and New Hampshire are filled with just his kind of voters â€” white and college educated â€” Buttigieg has struggled to build broader appeal among voters of color, a critical constituency in the partyâ€™s electorate. Heâ€™s down by double digits in recent polls of Nevada, a heavily Latino state, and is far behind the pack in South Carolina, a stronghold of critical black votes. Heâ€™ll need to capture their support or his moment could be fleeting.
The Buttigieg bus is a part of the same clever nostalgia play as his stump speech. The tour is a nod to John McCainâ€™s â€œStraight Talk Express,â€ which barreled through New Hampshire during the 2000 primary loaded with journalists and an off-the-cuff candidate. (Call Buttigiegâ€™s version a â€œschtickâ€ and you get a healthy eyeroll from his staff.) But Buttigieg isnâ€™t exactly an off-the-cuff guy, and his maneuvering to the top of the heap has been deliberate, seizing on the weaknesses of the two frontrunners, Biden and Warren. His â€œMedicare for All Who Want Itâ€ plan â€” basically a public option with a heavy dose of â€œwe wonâ€™t take away your private insurance and God-given freedomâ€ rhetoric â€” is a savvy play to the center. Itâ€™s meant to grant safe harbor to Democrats who think Warrenâ€™s Medicare for All plan is too radical a move. (Warren and Buttigieg voters are white and college educated, though her supporters tend to be much more ideologically liberal than his.) Warren-interested voters might be attracted to his sheen of intellectualism (the foreign languages, Oxford, yada, yada, yada) and some of the policy reforms heâ€™s suggested but rarely mentions on the stump these days, like getting rid of the Electoral College and changing the makeup of the Supreme Court.
He brought up these so-called â€œdemocracy reforms,â€ along with automation and K-12 education, when I asked him what heâ€™d like the primary campaign to be about besides just health care reform, an issue that has far and away come to dominate the race. Still, he conceded the role he believes health care has played in his rise. â€œThe value of the health care debate is it helps you see what it looks like to have a very progressive proposal thatâ€™s not as alienating or extreme as some of the alternatives. So to that extent, it helps me convey what weâ€™re trying to do in this campaign.â€
The campaignâ€™s message of moderation is one that, theoretically, could speak to black voters just as well as it does to Buttigiegâ€™s base of white ones. Black Democrats tend to identify as more moderate or conservative than white Democrats and so far in the primary, theyâ€™ve tended to lean toward Bidenâ€™s camp. And Buttigiegâ€™s rise once again has brought a hefty dose of criticism that he canâ€™t seem to appeal to voters of color.
When I asked what retail politics steps he was taking to appeal to black voters, Buttigieg brought up church visits â€” he thinks his faith is one central point of connection with black audiences â€” and an appeal to black sororities, which he called â€œa huge area of social capital.â€ But did he feel as if he was playing catch-up in forming relationships in the black community?
â€œWe need to engage a lot of folks in ways that are beyond the kind of visible on the record kind of appearances,â€ he said. â€œI think that thereâ€™s a level of catch up really throughout the whole campaign, just because I donâ€™t have years or decades of national exposure or Washington experience to lean on.â€ This lack of experience and his presumption to the office has grated on his rivals with longer resumes; several are quoted in a recent New York Times story with the headline, â€œWhy Pete Buttigieg Annoys His Democratic Rivals.â€
In the afternoon, the bus stopped in Stratham for a â€œbarn party,â€ which was like a regular old voter town hall, except held in an uninsulated barn in 26-degree weather. The candidate entered cinematically through doors draped in American flags and wore only a short leather jacket slightly reminiscent of Obamaâ€™s post-presidency â€œcool dadâ€ wardrobe. Buttigieg gave his speech and then it was time for questions. One woman, who was white â€” as was much of the crowd â€” stood up and expressed concern about Buttigiegâ€™s lack of appeal to black voters. How would he improve the criminal justice system, she asked? â€œThatâ€™s the problem they have.â€
