The event ended and the press corps hustled onto the warm bus for another hour-long drive. Reporters asked about his experience level, impeachment, the fact that he resonates so much with Boomers â€” â€œI sometimes wonder what a 19-year-old me would have thoughtâ€ â€” tax policy and health care. It was the third ride of the day, which meant it was the third time reporters had peppered Buttigieg with queries for an hour or so. At a certain point, even inquisitive journalists start to run out of earth-shattering questions. I asked what he was reading. A Roman history, a Seneca book â€” â€œitâ€™s very quotableâ€ he said of the stoic philosopher â€” and someone had given him James Baldwinâ€™s â€œThe Fire Next Time,â€ which he was rereading for the first time since college. â€œHis account of whiteness was very timely,â€ Buttigieg said. Did he think a lot about whiteness on the campaign trail, I asked? Was he able to appeal to swing voters â€” likely more conservative â€” in part because heâ€™s white (and theyâ€™re probably white too)?
â€œOne thing Iâ€™ve found, definitely engaging with white law enforcement officers back home, is the struggle in terms of the readiness of a lot of white folks to engage issues of race canâ€™t be overestimated,â€ he said. South Bendâ€™s police department and Buttigieg himself have been under scrutiny since the summer, when a white officer shot and killed Eric Logan, a 54-year-old black man. During a town hall held after the shooting, residents were openly confrontational with Buttigieg about his failures. â€œThe real problem I think is youâ€™ve got people who have a self-conception such that they can be horrified by the implications that they are in any way biased or racist having therefore a very hard time confronting the fact that everyone has biases. And added to that the fact that everyone has a race, everyoneâ€™s implicated in a racialized reality. But a huge part of whiteness, at least in America, is being able to not have to think about race much.â€
Implicitly, the conversation turned to interactions with voters, like the one in Stratham whoâ€™d made a comment about black Americans and â€œthe problem they haveâ€ with the criminal justice system.
