From a poll conducted Jan. 17-20, 2020, with 1,587 respondents.
It is likely not a coincidence that â€œwaste of timeâ€ is a phrase that Trump and his allies frequently use to describe the impeachment process. The news coverage of the impeachment process may also be driving some of what we see in our data. For example, respondents in our survey who said they mostly watched Fox News were much likelier than those who got their news from other sources to describe impeachment as a â€œwaste.â€ â€œSham,â€ â€œwitch huntâ€ and â€œstupidâ€ â€” all fixtures of Trumpâ€™s impeachment vocabulary â€” appeared with some regularity in Republicansâ€™ responses to the question.
Itâ€™s hard, of course, to know whether the growing perception among Republicans that impeachment is a â€œwasteâ€ is connected to some of the other trends weâ€™ve seen in our polling with Ipsos, including the fact that Republicansâ€™ support for Trump has grown, along with their skepticism about key elements of the Democratsâ€™ case against the president. But together, these trends indicate that over the past few months, at least some additional Republicans have fallen into line behind Trump. In fact, and as the chart below shows, Republicans are increasingly likely to use similar words to describe the impeachment process as compared to Democrats, who remain much less cohesive.
Democratsâ€™ most common responses are also noteworthy for what they didnâ€™t include. Words linked to the substance of the charges against Trump, like â€œUkraineâ€ or â€œquid pro quo,â€ werenâ€™t among those that were most frequently mentioned by Democrats. Instead, common descriptions hinged on the length of the process (â€œlongâ€ and â€œslowâ€), the figure at the center of the drama (â€œTrumpâ€ and â€œpresidentâ€), or the reasons for its existence (â€œnecessaryâ€ and â€œjusticeâ€). And about 5 percent of Democrats also used the word â€œwasteâ€ to describe impeachment, perhaps reflecting the not-insignificant number who think the process has been a bad use of Congressâ€™s time.
Polls can only tell us so much, of course, about how people are feeling â€” even when respondents are allowed to describe their perspective in their own words. But these findings do give us a window into how people on both sides of the impeachment debate are absorbing the process â€” and how they might continue to think about it after the final Senate vote is tallied. If nothing else, the fact that â€œwaste,â€ â€œTrumpâ€ and â€œpartisanâ€ are the only words that were frequently used by both Republicans and Democrats paints a fairly bleak picture of where Americans can find common ground when it comes to impeachment.\n|end|\n
