On the face of it, this isnâ€™t a great sign for Republicans. They are defending nine of these 14 seats and have eight incumbents running, so they should be in a better position to raise money than Democrats. But if we dig deeper, a race-by-race analysis shows these numbers are really a mixed bag for both parties.
For instance, a race where Republicans are considerably underwater is Kentucky, where Democrats have outraised Republicans by $4.6 million. Democrat Amy McGrath raised a remarkable $10.7 million in the third quarter. But even if McGrath continues to raise significantly more than Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, itâ€™s going to be very difficult to defeat him in strongly Republican Kentucky, especially with President Trump at the top of the ticket. Remember, too, McGrath raised a considerable amount of money in her 2018 House bid, but she still lost to the Republican incumbent by 3 points.
Unfortunately for Democrats, though, contributors donâ€™t necessarily put their money toward races where Democrats have the strongest chances of picking up a seat. Case in point: in North Carolina, a state Trump carried by less than 4 points in 2016, Republican Sen. Thom Tillis and other GOP candidates have outraised Democratic candidates nearly three-to-one so far. (And Tillis raised $3.6 of the GOPâ€™s $4.4 million, but he could have to spend a chunk of that in a potentially difficult primary against businessman Garland Tucker, who is doing a lot of self-funding.)
The races in Georgia, Iowa, Michigan and Texas also offered some positive financial indicators for the GOP. Republican Sens. David Perdue of Georgia, Joni Ernst of Iowa and John Cornyn of Texas led their Democratic opponents by between $700,000 and $1.6 million. And while Democratic Sen. Gary Peters of Michigan had more in total contributions â€” a nearly $2-million advantage in one of the GOPâ€™s better takeover opportunities â€” John James, the likely Republican nominee, actually outraised Peters in the third quarter, $3.1 million to $2.4 million.
Yet Democrats had good news, too, most notably in Arizona, which is shaping up to be a key battleground state in 2020. Retired astronaut Mark Kelly brought in $13.8 million, compared with appointed Republican Sen. Martha McSallyâ€™s $7.9 million. And unlike Kelly, McSally could have some primary trouble that forces her to spend money against her fellow Republicans and not just Kelly. And down South, Alabama Sen. Doug Jones, the most endangered Democratic incumbent, outraised his Republican counterparts by about $2 million. He will probably have to keep that up in order to have much of a chance in a state Trump won by about 28 points.
Itâ€™s tough to outraise incumbents, but Democrats also managed to stay close in both Colorado and Maine â€” the only states Republicans are defending that Hillary Clinton won in 2016. Former Colorado Gov. John Hickenlooper, who abandoned his presidential bid to run for Senate in August, attracted slightly more contributions in the third quarter than Republican Sen. Cory Gardner â€” $2.1 million to 1.9 million, for instance. (Although Gardner still had more in total contributions.) In the second quarter, Gardner had actually been substantially outraised by the Democratic field, but with Hickenlooperâ€™s entrance into the race, some leading Democrats dropped out, reducing Democratsâ€™ total contributions. Meanwhile, Republican Sen. Susan Collins of Maine brought in $700,000 more than the Democratic field, but Maine House Speaker Sara Gideon â€” the Democratsâ€™ leading candidate â€” still managed to outraise Collins by $1.1 million in the third quarter. Still, one plus for Collins and Gardner is that they donâ€™t have any primary opposition at the moment, unlike the Democrats in their states who will face crowded primaries.
There are also some lopsided numbers in a few other contests that are harder to make sense of. Democrats in Minnesota, New Hampshire and New Mexico have brought in far more than their Republican counterparts, which could make it tougher for the GOP to compete in those states. Meanwhile, Republicans hold a big lead in Kansas, but Republican-turned-Democrat Barbara Bollier jumped into the race in October, so the dynamics there could change, especially as Barry Grissom who had led in fundraising, with nearly $470,000 in the third quarter, dropped out and endorsed her.
In total, Democrats have continued their streak of outraising the GOP in these crucial contests, but each race tells its own story, and remember, a lot of money in the coffers doesnâ€™t necessarily amount to victory. Weâ€™ve still got a long way to go between now and Election Day 2020.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
Republicansâ€™ defense of President Trumpâ€™s pressure campaign with Ukraine has so far been much more about process than substance. Trumpâ€™s allies have talked a lot about the unfairness of the Democratsâ€™ impeachment inquiry, in which, as they tell it, Trump is a beleaguered defendant deprived of his due process rights. In the words of Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, Democrats have cut Trumpâ€™s lawyers â€œout of the process in an unprecedented way.â€
The basic sentiment is that the president is being railroaded. But the reality is that when it comes to impeachment, there arenâ€™t any protections for the president laid out in the Constitution. In fact, experts told me that pretty much any rights Democrats give Trump are above and beyond what theyâ€™re required to do. Trump hasnâ€™t been charged with a crime and impeachment isnâ€™t a legal proceeding, so he doesnâ€™t have any of the rights you hear about on â€œLaw and Order,â€ including due process. In the world of impeachment, â€œfairnessâ€ means whatever the majority party in the House of Representatives thinks it should mean.
This means the impeachment process is pretty much destined to give the president less power than he would like, and Trump is no exception. Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton also fought for their lawyers to have a bigger role in the proceedings, and ended up with the ability to participate in some way. Similarly, the impeachment resolution that passed Thursday did lay out some ground rules that include Trumpâ€™s legal team. As was the case in both Nixon and Clintonâ€™s impeachment proceedings, when the process moves to the Judiciary Committee, Trumpâ€™s lawyers will be able to cross-examine and suggest witnesses and present a formal defense.
But unlike previous impeachments, the first round of public hearings will happen in the House Intelligence Committee, where Trumpâ€™s legal team wasnâ€™t given a role, before the Judiciary Committee begins to weigh articles of impeachment. That might seem like a break from the past, but itâ€™s important to remember that House Democrats donâ€™t have a special counsel investigation to work from, and theyâ€™re still in the process of collecting and presenting evidence. That doesnâ€™t mean that Republicans wonâ€™t get some mileage out of continuing to hammer the Democratsâ€™ procedures as unfair. Impeachment may inevitably seem like something of a one-sided process â€” because thatâ€™s how it was designed.
Itâ€™s easy to see a presidential impeachment as something akin to a criminal prosecution â€” evidence is marshaled, a trial is held, and the presidentâ€™s fate hangs in the balance. But impeachment is a political process, not a legal one. As a result, it has entirely different rules that make certain protections that are reserved for criminal defendants â€” like due process â€” irrelevant. â€œAs a matter of law, a president has essentially no claim to any kind of participation in the impeachment process,â€ said Frank Bowman, a law professor at the University of Missouri and the author of â€œHigh Crimes and Misdemeanors: A History of Impeachment for the Age of Trump.â€
To be fair, the Constitution is pretty spare in its description of how impeachment works. It gives the â€œsole power of impeachmentâ€ to the House of Representatives and the â€œsole power to try impeachmentsâ€ to the Senate but it doesnâ€™t say much more, beyond the fact that Congressâ€™s power is limited to removing someone from office â€” a point the founders wanted to stress, since in England at the time, an impeachment conviction could lead to execution.
And there hasnâ€™t been much elaboration since. The Supreme Court weighed in on the Senateâ€™s procedures for impeaching judges back in 1993, but the justices ruled that the question of how the Senate was conducting its impeachment trials was a political one, and therefore beyond their power to decide. â€œThe consensus was that it would take something extraordinary, verging on deciding the outcome with a coin-flip, to allow the justices to intervene and say the Senate was doing things wrong,â€ Bowman said.
Trump isnâ€™t trying to take the House impeachment inquiry to the Supreme Court â€” at least, not yet. But Bowman said the bar for challenging the Houseâ€™s procedures would likely be even higher, because it doesnâ€™t have the power to remove anyone from office.
Of course, there are both high-minded and pragmatic reasons why Congress might want to allow the president to defend himself from impeachment â€” which is why Nixon, Clinton, and now Trump were all given some kind of role. After all, Trump is not the first president to claim that he is being treated unfairly, and a straightforward way to deflect that kind of criticism and shore up the perceived legitimacy of the process is to give the presidentâ€™s legal team a voice in the process.
The protections outlined for Trump and his legal team in the House resolution are actually pretty similar to the rules laid out for Nixon and Clinton, according to Sarah Binder, a political science professor at George Washington University who studies Congress. If the impeachment process makes its way to the House Judiciary Committee, which seems likely, Trumpâ€™s lawyers will be able to question and suggest witnesses, request evidence, and ask questions â€” just as Nixonâ€™s and Clintonâ€™s lawyers did before him.
All of these protections only kick in when impeachment moves into the Judiciary Committee, though â€” and unlike past impeachments, a significant portion of the action this time around will happen outside that committee. Importantly, Trumpâ€™s lawyers wonâ€™t be allowed to participate in the next phase of the inquiry, which will involve public hearings run by the House Intelligence Committee. But Binder said that made sense, because unlike the House majority in the Nixon and Clinton impeachments, Democrats donâ€™t have a voluminous special counsel probe to draw from, so the next round of hearings are arguably the public distillation of the Houseâ€™s investigation, not its case for impeachment. On a practical level, though, it means that Trumpâ€™s legal team likely wonâ€™t be able to get involved for several weeks â€” which leaves plenty of time for his defenders to complain about how heâ€™s been boxed out of the process.
Thereâ€™s one big caveat that didnâ€™t loom over past impeachment proceedings. The resolution specifies that those privileges can be yanked at any time if the Trump administration doesnâ€™t willingly cooperate with providing witnesses for testimony or documents. Itâ€™s a pointed addition, given that the Trump administration has so far issued a blanket refusal to cooperate with the inquiry, including blocking a raft of witnesses from appearing for testimony.
How the Trump administration uses its protections, of course, remains to be seen. Nixonâ€™s lawyer was integrally involved in the House Judiciary Committeeâ€™s investigations in 1974, although Clintonâ€™s lawyerâ€™s main appearance in Congress happened toward the end of the process, when the articles of impeachment had already been drafted. The Trump White House, to be sure, is still insisting the entire process is unconstitutional, and itâ€™s hard to imagine them changing their tune anytime soon.
But even if Democrats arenâ€™t actually prepared to follow through on their threat to cut off Trumpâ€™s lawyersâ€™ access to the hearings â€” which could appear to validate the criticisms of their process â€” itâ€™s a reminder that they are decidedly in the driverâ€™s seat. Trump might feel that the impeachment process is unfair, but if it is, itâ€™s because the Constitution made it that way.
