Welcome to Pollapalooza, our weekly polling roundup.
Very few Republican voters favor the impeachment and removal of President Trump â€” only about 11 percent, according to our impeachment polls tracker. Democrats voted on Thursday to move forward with public hearings on impeachment and will likely use the hearings to try to boost overall support for impeachment. But itâ€™s unlikely that impeachment gets much more popular without some Republican voters on board. So are GOP voters moveable?
Partisanship is as strong as ever, so itâ€™s unlikely we will see a huge shift â€” like a majority of Republicans suddenly supporting impeachment. But there are indications that â€” impeachment aside â€” GOP voters donâ€™t exactly approve of what Trump did with regard to Ukraine, so maybe some of them arenâ€™t fully entrenched in their views.
Most notably, a Selzer & Co./Grinnell College survey of U.S. adults released this week found that just 7 percent of respondents said that it is OK â€œfor political candidates in the U.S. to ask for assistance from a foreign government to help them win an election.â€ Eighty-one percent said it is not OK, including overwhelming majorities of people who live in rural areas (87 percent), evangelicals (85 percent) and Republicans (81 percent).
When pollsters mention Trumpâ€™s name in their questions, the results are more partisan. But even then, a solid bloc of Republicans object to Trumpâ€™s actions. A recent Suffolk University/USA Today poll found that nearly one-in-three Republicans said Trumpâ€™s phone conversation with the Ukrainian president was â€œwrong, but doesnâ€™t rise to an impeachable offenseâ€ (22 percent) or â€œan impeachable offenseâ€ (7 percent).1
Perhaps the most obvious explanation here is that many Republican voters donâ€™t necessarily agree with Trump pushing Ukraineâ€™s government to investigate former Vice President Joe Bidenâ€™s son but donâ€™t want him further investigated or removed from office. So the more a polling question raises the stakes and essentially requires respondents to say, â€œTrump is unfit for office and should be impeached,â€ the more likely Republican respondents are to align with the president.
An Economist/YouGov poll released this week fits this theory. The poll found that 14 percent of Republican adults think that Trump â€œpurposefullyâ€ withheld military aid from Ukraine to force an investigation into the Bidens, and another 23 percent said that they are unsure. That means only 63 percent of Republican respondents took the completely pro-Trump stance that the president did not intentionally withhold the money. Similarly, 15 percent of Republicans think that if itâ€™s proven that Trump withheld aid from the Ukrainians until they agreed to an investigation of the Bidens, that would constitute an impeachable offense. Another 20 percent say they arenâ€™t sure.
But that poll also found that Republicans are basically unified in opposing Trumpâ€™s impeachment (81 percent) or his removal (83 percent). Similarly, Morning Consult/Politico poll released this week found that only 11 percent of Republicans think that Trump â€œabused his power to influence the 2020 election,â€ while 73 percent said he was â€œacting within his power.â€
All this suggests a difficult path for Democrats to win over Republican voters on the subject of impeachment. Even if House lawmakers seize on some GOP votersâ€™ disapproval of Trumpâ€™s conduct in the abstract, they must overcome votersâ€™ strong loyalty to the president in selling impeachment.
According to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s presidential approval tracker, 41.1 percent of Americans approve of the job Trump is doing as president, while 54.1 percent disapprove (a net approval rating of -13 points). At this time last week, 41.6 percent approved and 54.0 percent disapproved (for a net approval rating of -12.4 points). One month ago, Trump had an approval rating of 41.5 percent and a disapproval rating of 53.5 percent, for a net approval rating of -12.0 points.
In our average of polls of the generic congressional ballot, Democrats currently lead by 5.5 percentage points (46.4 percent to 40.9 percent). At this time last week, Democrats led by 6.3 percentage points (46.6 percent to 40.3 percent). At this time last month, voters preferred Democrats by 6.7 points (46.8 percent to 39.9 percent).
