Joe Bidenâ€™s campaign has claimed he doesnâ€™t need to win Iowa and New Hampshire to become the Democratic presidential nominee. Instead, the former vice president has his eyes on states No. 3 and 4 on the primary calendar â€” Nevada and South Carolina â€” plus the 14 states that will vote on Super Tuesday, just three days after the South Carolina primary.
The logic makes a certain amount of sense, too. Biden polls better than other candidates among black and Hispanic voters, so the states after nearly-all-white Iowa and New Hampshire definitely play to his strengths, as theyâ€™re far more diverse and representative of the Democratic Party. Thereâ€™s just one problem: Since 1976, when the Iowa caucuses first became an influential part of the nomination process, the eventual Democratic nominee has almost always won either Iowa or New Hampshire (or both). In fact, thereâ€™s only one time this didnâ€™t happen â€” Bill Clinton in 1992, and the circumstances were unusual.1
But maybe thereâ€™s a case to be made that Iowa and New Hampshire donâ€™t matter as much for the Democrats as they once did. The states have never offered that many delegates, and their electorates donâ€™t look much like the modern Democratic Party. Arguably, winning South Carolinaâ€™s black voters or clinching California on Super Tuesday could matter a lot more. Of course, itâ€™s hard to argue that losing the first two states in the primary is a good strategy â€” and to be clear, the Biden campaign hasnâ€™t argued they donâ€™t want to win Iowa and New Hampshire, just that itâ€™s not essential. So does the Biden camp have a point? Letâ€™s go over the case for Iowa and New Hampshire mattering as much as they always have in the Democratic primary â€” and the case for their declining importance.
Following reforms to the primary system in the 1970s and Jimmy Carterâ€™s surprise victory in the 1976 Iowa caucuses, both Iowa and New Hampshire have become highly influential primary states, as they are the first two to vote (although there have been several unsuccessful efforts to change that).
