At this stage in the Democratic primary, many likely Democratic voters are still considering multiple candidates â€” and this was true for more than two-thirds of respondents in our poll with Ipsos. Which got us thinking, how many respondents were only considering one candidate?
FiveThirtyEight partnered with Ipsos to conduct a poll, using Ipsosâ€™s KnowledgePanel, that asked respondents who they were thinking about voting for and allowed them to pick multiple candidates (or â€œsomeone else,â€ or no one). And while most respondents in the post-debate round of polling were considering more than one candidate (66 percent of respondents), 33 percent only picked one candidate.1
And as you can see in the table below, about a fifth of former Vice President Joe Bidenâ€™s supporters werenâ€™t considering supporting anyone else, a higher share of exclusive supporters than any other candidate. Likewise, 14.6 percent of Sen. Bernie Sandersâ€™s potential supporters werenâ€™t looking anywhere else.
Share of each candidatesâ€™ supporters who are only considering voting for that candidate, according to a FiveThirtyEight/Ipsos poll
*Only considering one candidate
From a survey of 1,761 likely Democratic primary voters who were surveyed from Oct. 15 to Oct. 16.
So what do we make of the fact that such a high share of Bidenâ€™s and Sandersâ€™s potential supporters were only considering them? Itâ€™s definitely a good sign for their campaigns, as it might be harder for other candidates to win these voters over. But itâ€™s also not the only way to understand the strength of someoneâ€™s campaign, especially at this early stage in the primary. If youâ€™re a candidate, getting a lot of voters to at least consider supporting you is important, too, as it means youâ€™re still in the hunt for their vote, and the other candidates on a voterâ€™s list tells you something about what parts of the party your message is appealing to.
Overall, more respondents were considering Biden than Sen. Elizabeth Warren (56.5 to 52.1 percent), but Warren actually shares a lot of potential supporters with the other candidates. Take the rest of the top five candidates â€” Biden, Sanders, Sen. Kamala Harris and South Bend, Indiana, Mayor Pete Buttigieg. The lionâ€™s share of voters who were considering each of those four were also considering Warren â€” even though Biden had more total potential supporters. Sanders was also being considered, but the percentage of respondents who also chose him wasnâ€™t as large.
And it isnâ€™t just among the top five candidates whose potential supporters were also thinking about Warren. For all but three candidates â€” Rep. Tulsi Gabbard, Sen. Amy Klobuchar and billionaire Tom Steyer â€” the person they were most likely to share potential supporters with was Warren. (Gabbard shares the most potential supporters with Sanders and businessman Andrew Yang, while Klobuchar and Steyer share the most with Biden.)
Itâ€™s clear Warren appeals to a wide range of Democratic voters, which puts her in a good position to gain supporters if another candidate drops out of the race. But sheâ€™s not alone in that position â€” just as many potential supporters of other candidates are considering Warren, many of Warrenâ€™s potential supporters are considering other candidates. So if Warrenâ€™s campaign were to run into trouble, candidates like Biden, Sanders, Buttigieg and Harris could stand to benefit.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
In the fall of 1998, it seemed like President Clinton was in trouble. An investigation by independent counsel Kenneth Starr had uncovered an affair between the president and White House intern Monica Lewinsky. And after months of denials, Clinton finally admitted to having had â€œan inappropriate relationshipâ€ with Lewinsky, which was then recounted in graphic detail in the report Starr sent to Congress. The affair and the presidentâ€™s attempts to hide it were quickly denounced by Republicans and Democrats alike. In a speech on the Senate floor, then-Democratic Sen. Joe Lieberman said Clintonâ€™s conduct was â€œdisgracefulâ€ and â€œimmoral.â€ Just a few weeks later, the House voted to open an impeachment inquiry, with the support of 31 Democrats.
Months later, though, Clinton hadnâ€™t just survived the impeachment process â€” he had managed to weather it with high approval ratings and the backing of his party. Despite bipartisan rumblings of displeasure with the president as the inquiry took off, public support never really coalesced behind impeachment, and the effort was ultimately perceived by many as a partisan attack by House Republicans bent on taking down a political opponent.
So as the Democrats plunge forward with their impeachment inquiry, Clintonâ€™s failed impeachment looms as a cautionary tale. After all, no Republicans at this point have come out in support of an impeachment inquiry, which means Democrats will arguably have even more work to do to convince the public that the allegations against President Trump arenâ€™t merely political. And although support for impeachment is on the upswing, itâ€™s hard to predict if that will last â€” or if public opinion will just ossify along familiar partisan lines, as it did during Clintonâ€™s impeachment.
Itâ€™s tempting to think of Trumpâ€™s impeachment as a sequel of sorts, but there are already signs that whatâ€™s happening today could unfold quite differently. For one thing, the case against Clinton hinged on the findings in Starrâ€™s report. By contrast, todayâ€™s Democrats didnâ€™t choose to orient their inquiry around findings in special counsel Robert Muellerâ€™s report that examined misconduct by Trump: They are instead building a case against the president in real time, which makes it harder to predict where the public will ultimately land.
And although thereâ€™s still a significant risk that the investigation will be perceived as partisan, the nature of the allegations against Trump are quite different. Many Americans saw Clintonâ€™s affair with Lewinsky as a â€œprivate matter,â€ but Trump pressuring Ukraine to investigate the son of Democratic presidential candidate Joe Biden is much more clearly tied to his role as commander-in-chief. So itâ€™s entirely possible that the public will be less forgiving this time.
By the time the House of Representatives voted to open an impeachment inquiry against Clinton in October 1998, the allegations against the president had been in the news for months. Clinton had publicly confessed to the affair in August, and in mid-September, Starr delivered his lengthy and salacious report â€” which included a case for impeaching Clinton â€” to Congress.
At that moment, support for impeachment seemed like it might be on the upswing. A Gallup poll conducted in mid-October, just after the House voted to formally open an impeachment inquiry, found that 48 percent of the public supported the decision to hold hearings. But as the chart below shows, support for impeachment didnâ€™t continue to tick upward. In mid-December, when the House voted to impeach Clinton on two counts of perjury and obstruction of justice, just about 40 percent of the public continued to think he should be impeached â€” and the same was true in February, when the Senate voted to acquit him.
This didnâ€™t stop Republicans from raking Clinton over the coals in the lead-up to the 1998 midterm elections, though. Thatâ€™s perhaps because there was one segment of the public that did see an uptick in support for impeachment â€” Republican voters. In mid-August 1998, an ABC News poll found that only 38 percent of Republicans thought Clinton should be impeached and removed from office. But by the time the House had voted to impeach him, about two-thirds of Republicans were on board. The GOPâ€™s attacks, though, didnâ€™t seem to have the effect of boosting overall support for impeachment; if anything, it just resulted in a widening partisan divide.
Clintonâ€™s presidential approval ratings were also high when the scandal started to unravel, and they remained remarkably undented throughout the impeachment process. Approval of his job performance had been hovering between 60 and 70 percent through most of 1998, and with the exception of a small dip around the time the Starr report was released in September, they stayed above 60 percent. In fact, according to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s tracker of presidential approval, Clintonâ€™s approval ratings hit 67 percent at the end of December 1998, just after he was impeached by the House. It was among the highest job approval ratings he received at any point in his administration.
There were other signs, too, that the public didnâ€™t think Clinton should be removed from office. Republicansâ€™ efforts to impeach Clinton appeared to be dramatically backfiring in real time â€” after running a slew of ads attacking Clinton in the lead-up to the midterms, they lost seats and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who had been one of Clintonâ€™s loudest critics, resigned the speakership.
That electoral loss has been woven, over the years, into a cautionary fable about the costs of impeachment without broad public support. But, of course, Clinton himself didnâ€™t emerge unscathed â€” Americans generally disapproved of his handling of the scandal and questioned his integrity, and those sentiments may have hurt Democrats in the 2000 election. So while itâ€™s difficult to evaluate whether the Republicans or the Democrats paid more of a price in the long term, the impeachment process clearly left a mark on both.
It wasnâ€™t always clear that Democrats would stand by Clinton. Some distanced themselves from the president in the lead-up to the midterm elections; others even questioned whether he should resign. The initial vote to refer Starrâ€™s report to the House Judiciary Committee for further investigation passed by an overwhelming margin. And when the House voted a few weeks later to open a formal impeachment inquiry, 31 moderate Democrats were in support. â€œMany Democrats were angry and frustrated that their leader had lied to them,â€ said Julian Zelizer, a professor of history and public affairs at Princeton University. â€œThat softened them to the idea of at least having an investigation.â€
But after a fairly brief period, the House was divided once again into familiar partisan camps. By the time the House voted on the articles of impeachment against Clinton just five Democrats voted to impeach the president. And when it was the Senateâ€™s turn to decide whether Clinton should remain in office, only Republicans crossed the aisle, with 10 GOP senators voting to acquit Clinton on at least one of the charges.
Why did Democrats fall in line behind Clinton? The Republicansâ€™ aggressive pursuit of impeachment â€” even in the absence of a clear public consensus â€” may have pushed Democrats to close ranks. â€œA significant number of Democrats thought there should be some consequence for Clintonâ€™s behavior, like a formal censure vote,â€ said Philip Bobbitt, a professor of law at Columbia University and the coauthor of â€œImpeachment: A Handbook.â€ â€œBut when it became clear that the Republicans were just going for impeachment, they became much more defensive.â€
Clinton also did damage control of his own. After first trying to quickly move past the scandal, he delivered an extravagant apology for his conduct on the day Starrâ€™s report was released, saying he had â€œsinnedâ€ and â€œrepented.â€ That apparent contrition may have helped some Democrats rally around him, although others remained angry with him throughout the process. As late as February, Sen. Dianne Feinstein â€” who months earlier had said her confidence in Clintonâ€™s credibility was â€œshatteredâ€ by the revelation of the affair â€” pushed for a bipartisan vote in the Senate to censure Clinton. But as upset as Democrats might have been with Clinton for having the affair, or for trying to conceal it, they continued to support the president, bolstered by the fact that public opinion was largely on their side.
â€œBy the end, very few Democrats, even if they disliked Clinton, were willing to say his behavior was worthy of impeachment,â€ Zelizer said. â€œAnd many Republicans in the Senate had the same misgivings.â€
Itâ€™s dangerous to draw too many parallels between what happened then and whatâ€™s occurring in Congress now. For one thing, the Democrats are still in the early stages of their inquiry. But experts told me that there are some lessons for todayâ€™s Democrats in the story of Clintonâ€™s impeachment.
First, there is the risk that, like the Republicans in Clintonâ€™s impeachment, the Democratsâ€™ investigation into Trump could be seen primarily as an attack on a political adversary. Starrâ€™s investigation was seen as politically motivated, and the Republicans relied almost entirely on his findings, without trying to marshal evidence of their own. â€œThis was a process that was perceived as partisan and rushed, with very few hearings and no revelation more shocking than the fact that the president had lied,â€ Zelizer said. And when House Republicans pressed ahead â€” even after it was clear from public opinion polls and the results of the 1998 midterms that much of the public just wasnâ€™t convinced by their arguments â€” it only reinforced the perception that their true motivation was to hurt Clinton.
Some of these risks are obviously present for Democrats today. With no committed Republican support so far, itâ€™s very difficult to argue that there arenâ€™t partisan elements to the investigation. And as with the Clinton impeachment, Republicans and Democrats are deeply divided about the presidentâ€™s conduct, which could make it difficult to build a true consensus around impeachment.
The Democratsâ€™ inquiry is different, though, in that they donâ€™t have a completed investigation like Starrâ€™s. Democrats had an opportunity to frame an impeachment inquiry around a completed special counsel investigation after the exhaustive findings in Muellerâ€™s report became public, but only moved forward with impeachment after the Ukraine allegations presented a new scandal and an evolving set of facts to pursue. As a result, they may be able to avoid (or at least mitigate) the perception that they were just looking for an excuse to impeach Trump, especially as new evidence continues to emerge.
And while the allegations against Clinton were personal and moral, the conduct at issue in Trumpâ€™s case is much more closely linked to his power as president, which could mean the public will be less inclined to dismiss it as human error. â€œWith Clinton I think a lot of people looked at themselves in a mirror and said, â€˜You know, Iâ€™d lie about my affair too,â€™â€ said Jeffrey Engel, a presidential historian at Southern Methodist University. â€œPressuring a foreign power to investigate a political adversary is a lot less relatable.â€
Itâ€™s too early to say whether any of these parallels will hold true. But while the risks are certainly there, the Democrats are still building their case. And they also have this history as a guide â€” which means they may be able to avoid some of their predecessorsâ€™ mistakes, rather than repeating them.
Nathaniel Rakich contributed research.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
The still-very-crowded Democratic presidential primary has been polled pretty extensively this year, giving observers a sense of whoâ€™s doing well in their efforts to win over likely Democratic primary voters and caucusgoers and who is having a hard time gaining traction. And the polls have been shifting gradually over the last few months: Former Vice President Joe Biden retains his first-place standing while Sen. Elizabeth Warren continues to make slow and steady progress, and Sen. Bernie Sanders has slipped somewhat, although he has maintained support in the mid-teens for some time.
But despite many months of campaigning, there still isnâ€™t a clear party consensus â€” thereâ€™s a clear top tier of candidates, but no runaway leader has emerged. So in a field this large, we have turned to asking people who they donâ€™t want the Democratic nominee to be. One of us (Masket) has been doing this as part of his early-state activist interviews since April, and the other (Peterson) included this question in a recent survey he conducted with Iowa State University/Civiqs among likely Iowa Democratic caucusgoers. (Peterson is planning to ask the question again in followup surveys.) To be sure, our approaches measure different things â€” the preferences of a few dozen party activists arenâ€™t necessarily the same as those of several hundred caucus goers â€” but we have found some similar patterns.
For starters, one of the most notable features of this primary field is just how many people donâ€™t want to see Sanders as the nominee even though heâ€™s currently third in the national polls. Obviously Sanders is backed by an enthusiastic set of supporters, but weâ€™ve also found that he has a substantial number of detractors in the party. In Masketâ€™s August early-state activist interviews, 59 percent of activists (17 of 29 people interviewed) said they did not want him to be the nominee (compared with 21 percent â€” 6 people â€” who said they were considering supporting him); only Miramar, Florida, Mayor Wayne Messam and Rep. Tulsi Gabbard earned worse marks (62 percent â€” 18 people â€” did not want either of them to be the nominee). Meanwhile, in that Iowa State University/Civiqs poll, 25 percent said they didnâ€™t want to see Sanders as the nominee (compared with 16 percent who listed him as their first choice), giving him the second-worst marks of any candidate on this question.
The suggestion here is that Sanders is a factional candidate; a specific set of Democrats are very excited about him, but he has limited ability to expand that coalition into a broader base of support. For instance, in that Iowa State University/Civiqs poll, Sanders has struggled to win over new supporters â€” among those who didnâ€™t back him in 2016, less than 1 percent want to see him become the nominee in 2020, and a third specifically do not want to see him nominated. Of course, that doesnâ€™t mean Sanders cannot win the nomination â€” President Trump was arguably a factional candidate for much of the 2016 cycle â€” but it does mean Sandersâ€™s potential for growth is limited.
Another candidate with a substantial number of detractors is â€¦ Biden. Thatâ€™s right, even though he still sits near the top of the polls, he was the No. 1 candidate who likely Democratic voters said they did not want to see as the nominee (30 percent) in that Iowa State University/Civiqs poll. Likewise, in Masketâ€™s August early-state activist survey, 31 percent (9 people) of those interviewed said they did not want to see Biden become the nominee. Granted, this was not anywhere close to the percentages who said they didnâ€™t want Messam, Gabbard, or Sanders nominated, but it was still quite high given how many activists also said they were still considering Biden (34 percent, or 10 people).
It may be harder to think of Biden as a factional candidate than Sanders, given that Biden also enjoys significant support among a broad swath of demographic groups within the party, including a majority of African American voters. But heâ€™s nonetheless facing a situation in which, if he did win, he might be a relatively controversial nominee who alienates some wings of the party or has trouble generating enthusiasm that can translate into voter turnout.
To be clear, this doesnâ€™t mean Sanders and Biden are actively disliked by the party; both of them actually have high favorability ratings â€” 73 percent and 72 percent of Democrats had favorable opinions of Biden and Sanders, according to an average of national August polls by FiveThirtyEightâ€™s Nathaniel Rakich. And if you look at Iowa surveys that also ask this question, Democrats have a fairly favorable view of both Biden and Sanders. But our question is different â€” weâ€™re not asking whether respondents like a candidate; weâ€™re asking who they donâ€™t want to win the nomination. And while that question might capture some candidates who people dislike, itâ€™s also entirely plausible that many Democrats like Biden and Sanders but still donâ€™t want them to be the nominee.
Of course, itâ€™s also plausible that Biden and Sanders experience more opposition than the other candidates because people simply know more about them â€” they both have high name recognition and long histories in politics. We found that candidates without such histories, like Warren and former Housing and Urban Development Secretary JuliÃ¡n Castro, werenâ€™t really opposed yet by early-state activists or Iowa caucusgoers. This could change, though, as Warrenâ€™s new status as a front-runner means a good deal of criticism and media attention will be aimed at her, and the number of Democrats uncomfortable with her as the nominee may well rise.
One other thing to keep in mind is that itâ€™s not entirely clear how strong this opposition to Biden or Sanders actually is. And thatâ€™s because this is a comparison among other Democratic candidates â€” and not a comparison to, say, Trump. Democrats care a lot about winning this year, so if either Sanders or Biden were to win the nomination, Democratic activists and voters who donâ€™t want to see them as the nominee may still rally behind them. But it makes sense that the party would want a nominee who can speak to all of its key constituencies, or at least not alienate many of them. So as Democrats look to find a candidate who can not only keep the party together but also keep the partyâ€™s supporters enthusiastic about voting in 2020, they canâ€™t afford to ignore the fact that some potential nominees are disliked by a substantial portion of the party.\n|end|\n
