As the Ukraine scandal continues to dominate the headlines, former Vice President Joe Biden remains the most-mentioned candidate on cable news. But even though Biden has been getting so much attention, Sen. Elizabeth Warren has been slowly and steadily rising in popularity (although not at his expense). Last Tuesday, Warren surpassed Biden in the RealClearPolitics average of polls for the first time. It should come as no surprise, then, that Warren is the next most-mentioned candidate on cable news after Biden and that her share of coverage increased last week from the previous week, according to data from the TV News Archive,1 which chops up TV news into 15-second clips. Though this column typically also includes data from Media Cloud, a database of online news stories, that data is temporarily unavailable due to site maintenance.
Share of 15-second cable news clips mentioning each candidate
Includes all candidates that qualify as â€œmajorâ€ in FiveThirtyEightâ€™s rubric. Each networkâ€™s daily news coverage is chopped up into 15-second clips, and each clip that includes a candidateâ€™s name is counted as one mention. Our search queries look for an exact match for each candidateâ€™s name, except for JuliÃ¡n Castro, for whom our search query is â€œJulian Castroâ€ OR â€œJuliÃ¡n Castro.â€ Percentages are calculated as the number of clips mentioning each candidate divided by the number of clips mentioning any of the 2020 Democratic contenders for that week.
Sources: Internet Archiveâ€™s Television News Archive via the GDELT Project
But Warrenâ€™s rise in coverage isnâ€™t all about how well sheâ€™s doing in the polls, and itâ€™s also not evenly distributed across the three networks that we monitor (CNN, Fox News and MSNBC). This week she was mentioned in 327 clips on Fox News, but only 176 on MSNBC and 108 on CNN, marking the second week in a row that she has been mentioned significantly more on Fox News compared to the other networks.
And itâ€™s not just the amount of coverage that differs. Fox News is also focusing on stories that the other two networks are not devoting as much time to. â€œHillary Clintonâ€ and â€œvisibly pregnantâ€ are among the top three two-word phrases most particular to Fox News in clips about Elizabeth Warren last week.2 The phrase â€œHillary Clintonâ€ â€” which appeared in 17 clips on Fox that mentioned Warren, but only two on each CNN and MSNBC â€” appeared often in segments about Clintonâ€™s response to a tweet from President Trump suggesting Clinton should run for president and â€œsteal it awayâ€ from Warren. And the phrase â€œvisibly pregnant,â€ which appeared in 14 Fox News clips last week but wasnâ€™t mentioned at all on CNN or MSNBC, occurred in segments about Warrenâ€™s response to allegations that she misrepresented the details of her departure from a job as a special education teacher in the early 1970s.
If Warren continues to rise in the polls, she could get more media attention (and scrutiny) than she has in the past. Weâ€™ll be monitoring just how much attention she gets in cable and online news, and whether the amount and content continues to diverge across different media sources. Stay tuned!
