A couple of months ago, I found myself in the curious position of examining Joe Bidenâ€™s head.
On television, the former vice president comes across as perpetually tanned and coiffed â€” always with the aviator glasses and the crisp shirtsleeves. He still works out every morning, often lifting weights and riding a Peloton bike, and his face is still golden, his brow remarkably unfurrowed for a man of his 76 years. Up close â€” like, six inches up close â€” Biden is slighter than you might imagine. From my aft position in a press gaggle in Dearborn, Michigan, I could see the baby-pink of his scalp peeking through wisps of gleaming white hair and the faint mottling near his ears. They caught me off guard, all those fragile little human details you miss on television.
And it was a very human summer for Biden, if youâ€™re going by â€œto err is humanâ€ standards. On June 18, speaking at a New York City fundraiser at the Carlyle Hotel (a swank spot on the Upper East Side where Woody Allen has a standing gig to play jazz clarinet), Biden began talking about the need for consensus-building. According to the pool report, he broke into a southern drawl as he brought up a segregationist senator from Mississippi: â€œI was in a caucus with James O. Eastland,â€ Biden said. â€œHe never called me â€˜boy,â€™ he always called me â€˜son.â€™â€ Herman Talmadge â€” â€œone of the meanest guys I ever knewâ€ â€” was another southern segregationist Democrat who Biden worked with. â€œWell guess what? At least there was some civility. We got things done. We didnâ€™t agree on much of anything. We got things done. We got it finished.â€
