Something about the man himself seems to be resonating with black voters, too. Rep. James Clyburn of South Carolina, a Democratic power broker, told me that Bidenâ€™s greatest asset with black voters might well be his own life story, which is strewn with personal tragedy. â€œWe can be no more noble than what our experiences allow us to be. And black voters, by and large, see so much of their experiences in Joe Biden.â€
The cornerstone of Bidenâ€™s candidacy is support from the black community and his long-standing relationships in it. In June, he attended Rep. James Clyburnâ€™s â€œWorld Famous Fish Fryâ€ and spoke to Rev. Al Sharpton.
WIN MCNAMEE / SEAN RAYFORD / GETTY IMAGES
But while Joseph Robinette Biden, the Irish-American speaker of self-conscious Scrantonese, is black votersâ€™ current choice in a Democratic primary featuring two viable black candidates, thereâ€™s a sense that the winds could shift at any moment. He spent the better part of the summer relitigating his decades-long voting record. His opponents have pressed him on what they say is an antiquated outlook on race relations in America, all in an effort to chip away at his support among people of color. Prominent Democrats openly fret that he might be too old for the job. The supposed ephemera has accumulated against him even as the numbers check out nicely on paper.
The oddity for present-day Joe Biden is that he was sure America already knew him and what he was all about. But the politics of 2019â€™s Democratic Party can be slipshod and capricious. Its candidates are viewed more often than not through a kaleidoscopic refraction of peoplesâ€™ frustrations with the system or their anger at the president. Biden isnâ€™t really â€œUncle Joeâ€ these days, but he presents a pretty enough picture; squint and youâ€™ll see the halcyon Democratic era of the Obamas. If things stay that way â€” for black voters most especially â€” Biden might yet win a presidential nomination. But one or two ticks off the mark and the colors and patterns all change. Suddenly Biden could look like a wholly different man.
Bidenâ€™s current resonance with black voters is perhaps chiefly owed to Obama, a man he once called â€œthe first mainstream African American who is articulate and bright and clean and a nice-looking guy.â€
In one sense itâ€™s ironic that Bidenâ€™s Achilles heel is the past, since a central argument of his campaign is that he can turn back the clock â€” but not too far back. He wants voters to remember him from the placid (by comparison) days of the Obama administration. Further back in Bidenâ€™s past, things get iffier. To that end, it is Obamaâ€™s name that Biden seems to mention most on the campaign trail â€” so much so that at the recent NAACP national convention, moderator April Ryan asked Biden if he used the former president as a â€œcrutch.â€ (The answer was no. He then went on to talk about Obama some more.) Obama, it should be noted, is wildly popular among Democrats these days â€” a Gallup post-presidency poll found that he had a 95 percent favorability rating.
The continued Obama name-dropping might have seemed cringeworthy following Bidenâ€™s opponentsâ€™ critiques â€” verging on an I-have-black-friends line of defense â€” but it was also powerful. Many black voters buy the idea that if Biden was good enough for Obama, Bidenâ€™s good enough for them. Sheila Hill, an NAACP convention attendee from Arlington, Texas, was emblematic of many voters when she put her fondness of Biden in familial terms: â€œJoe came up like heâ€™s a member of the family, like he might sit down and have a bite to eat, pull him up a plate, let him get some greens and cornbread. And you know how everyone was introduced? He didnâ€™t need to introduce himself because heâ€™s part of the family.â€ 
A lynchpin of the Biden campaignâ€™s strategy is embracing President Obamaâ€™s legacy whenever possible.
