Biden isnâ€™t alone, of course. Thereâ€™s a moral imperative for each of the top three primary contenders, all in their 70s. Bernie Sanders and Warren proffer a promise of a golden, hopeful new system; Biden the restoration of one that was pretty good, if not perfect. If anything, the Democratic primary is something of a paean to old age, to lifelong ambitions and vocations yet to be fulfilled. Itâ€™s a monthslong slog as a trio of older white people bid to lead a country more black and brown than itâ€™s ever been. I can see them â€” with more years behind them than ahead, in a world so different from the one they were born into â€” lingering longer than the rest of us over the most hashed-out lines of Tennysonâ€™s â€œUlyssesâ€:
