Iâ€™ve spent a couple of days in New Hampshire this past week and keep on realizing Iâ€™ve already been places. I pulled into a brewery at the end of a dark, windy road (is everything out of a Robert Frost poem up here?) and recognized the refurbished barn from another candidateâ€™s tour of the place. I drove up to my hotel and remembered that Iâ€™d eaten in its restaurant four years ago. The snow is the same as in 2016, too; big flakes that catch in your eye and make you wish youâ€™d thought to bring waterproof mascara.
A lot of the voter talk is the same as four years ago, too. Namely all the cynicism and worry â€” Whatâ€™s the matter with America? and Whatâ€™s the matter with the media? kind of stuff. The only thing thatâ€™s different this year is that itâ€™s coming from Democrats.
When you see candidates campaigning or voters listening to a stump speech, you donâ€™t see a lot of unbridled merriment or excitement. Instead itâ€™s a business-like frenzy to, as Democrats see it, pull the country back from the brink.
â€œItâ€™s horrible to say but thereâ€™s more dumb people than I realized, or gullible people that donâ€™t listen,â€ Catherine Michel, 69, told me. We were standing flush to a wall in a VFW hall in Somersworth, watching a Joe Biden event break up. The former vice president had arrived in the gray morning light in his aviator sunglasses, lenses that have been glued to Bidenâ€™s face quite a bit these days as he looks to project the cool that seems to be rapidly leaving him with every passing poll.
Michel was there with her husband, David, and they were anxious to see Biden before they made their choice. They couldnâ€™t bear to see President Donald Trump on TV anymore. â€œHe reminds me of Mussolini giving a speech, how he juts his jaw out and cocks his face,â€ David said. The Michels wanted to know what candidate could puncture that air of abrasive confidence in the president. â€œTrump is that dishonest bully and dishonest bullies often win,â€ Catherine said. â€œItâ€™s really scary. So while I might support Bernie Sanders as the guy to stand up against a bully with lots of energy and just die punching him, is that the way to go? Or pick someone in the middle?â€
Jim and Mary from Dover, 78 and 74, stood outside waiting to see Biden board his bus. Both said they would vote for the former vice president, but theyâ€™d entertained other options â€” Mary had been impressed with Amy Klobucharâ€™s performance during the Brett Kavanaugh Supreme Court nomination hearings. But Jim, a former registered Republican, said the senator from Minnesota didnâ€™t stand a chance in the 2020 fray. â€œIn normal times, she might have a chance, right? But this is a war. This is not a nice political process. This is a war and the poor Democrats think theyâ€™re going to have a political process and a campaign, and Trump is just gonna fight dirtier than anybody can fight,â€ he said. He brought up a friend who likes Rush Limbaugh â€” Jim is not a fan â€” and I asked if he thought the countryâ€™s political climate was in part the fault of the media. â€œNo, itâ€™s a citizen problem,â€ he said. â€œIf you watch a cable program with these terrible slams, then you have to make a point of watching the other slams. Then you blend the two and hopefully you read a newspaper somewhere.â€
