A few hours later, voters in North Hampton nursed beers as they waited for actress Ashley Judd, an Elizabeth Warren surrogate, to arrive. But those at one table I approached hadnâ€™t realized theyâ€™d walked into a political event. John and Deanna of Hollis, 67 and 58, were friendly, but John told me heâ€™d given me a fake last name â€” media distrust is a constant theme on the trail. Far from seeking out the political, the couple told me their Republican friends donâ€™t even know theyâ€™re Democrats. They only talk politics to each other these days, so as not to rock the boat. â€œAll it would take was one conversation to blow that all up,â€ John said. He said itâ€™s uncomfortable for them because their friends â€œtalk like everyone feels the same wayâ€ about Trump and politics. Lately, John has found that people make assumptions about what youâ€™re OK with. Heâ€™d been on a work trip in Texas and, â€œI sat in a car with a group of people that were customers and I heard them make racial comments and a few years back they wouldnâ€™t have.â€
