Iâ€™d seen the email for the event. I think I thought the drive was too far, simple as that. If Iâ€™m really being honest, I didnâ€™t think about it all that much. Probably because American men do kill American women so often and probably because men have been killing the women they know and love since the dawn of time. Sad, but wholly typical. But it was lacerating to hear the statistic in that cozy New Hampshire bar; you are alive and they are not.
Whatâ€™s so often lost in the primary rush â€” the horserace ups and downs â€” is the primary reason for government: a need to regulate ourselves, to instill order and some semblance of justice in society. But justice is often as wide as the chancellorâ€™s foot â€” which is to say, wholly unjust. Still, the sense that society has to wrangle some order is agreed upon. What elections are about is what sort of order to instill â€” economic, diplomatic, militaristic.
Sometimes the little things like keeping people alive gets lost in the shuffle. So too do our individual sensibilities â€” everything becomes so zoomed out that you can only see a mass of people moving one way or the other, not the component parts. Itâ€™s easier to tell that story on television or in 1,200 words.
Catherine Michelâ€™s father was a Trump supporter. He passed away, but when she spoke about him, it was in the present tense, since parents are always on your shoulder, wherever you are. She was explaining to me, I think, that he wasnâ€™t defined by the last presidential candidate he supported. â€œHe raised five girls and a boy. Heâ€™s very democratic and loving and liberal and education for the minorities and charity and global warming, of course,â€ she said. â€œBut then when he listens â€” the media. â€¦â€ She sort of paused, looking for the words. â€œThe media has to be really careful.â€\n|end|\n
