Day-by-day results of the 7 News/Emerson College tracking poll of New Hampshire, Jan. 31 â€“ Feb. 6, 2020
Source: 7 News/Emerson College
Since the final poll before the Iowa caucuses â€” which took place on Feb. 3, although the results have been announced slowly over the course of the entire week â€” Buttigieg has gained 12 points in the Suffolk poll and 10 points in the Emerson poll. The Suffolk poll implies he is getting this support from Biden, who has dropped 7 points since Feb. 2-3, although the Emerson poll doesnâ€™t show nearly as significant a dropoff for the former vice president â€” so maybe Buttigiegâ€™s claim of victory in Iowa is just causing undecided voters to finally settle on him as their choice.
And there is still plenty of room for Buttigieg (or another candidate â€” if, say, someone else has a good debate on Friday) to gain. According to Marist, 15 percent of likely Democratic primary voters who have a preferred candidate say they still might change their minds, and 5 percent say they are still outright undecided.
Just because Buttigieg has the momentum in New Hampshire, however, doesnâ€™t mean his chances of winning the nomination have increased. Our overall primary forecast still gives Buttigieg only a 1 in 25 (4 percent) chance of winning a majority of pledged delegates. In a nutshell, proving you can (partially) win Iowa and (maybe) win New Hampshire doesnâ€™t prove you can win more diverse states like Nevada and South Carolina â€” and Buttigieg is still underperforming with nonwhite voters, although weâ€™d like to see more post-Iowa national polls to confirm this.
