micah: Amelia, I think Leeâ€™s article speaks to that:
The insight here borrows from political scientist Timur Kuranâ€™s classic work Private Truth, Public Lies: The Social Consequences of Preference Falsification. The logic is straightforward: In social and political situations, people often have private preferences that are costly to express. So they keep quiet to maintain social status or sometimes personal safety. They say and do what they think they are supposed to say and do to get along. Hence, the â€œPublic Liesâ€ part of the title.
But sometimes the calculus changes. Sometimes a critical mass expresses a dangerous opinion. This empowers others to speak up. Then even more folks feel empowered. And then even more. And then there is a social revolution.
So, in theory, if Republicans reach a critical mass of members who want to defect â€” and I have no idea if we will reach that mass or how big that mass has to be â€” GOP defections could sorta happen all at once.
