While Warren took the No. 2 spot in media mentions for the week (which includes the days leading up to the debate), if we look only at data from the two full days of coverage after the debate ended,3 former Rep. Beto Oâ€™Rourke was mentioned in more in 15-second cable news clips than Warren across the three channels we monitor â€” CNN, Fox News and MSNBC. During the debate, Oâ€™Rourke said â€œHell yes, weâ€™re going to take your AR-15, your AK-47. Weâ€™re not going to allow it to be used against our fellow Americans anymore.â€ Those comments loomed large in the media coverage of the debate: 38 percent of 15-second cable news clips that mentioned Oâ€™Rourke during that time also mentioned â€œgunâ€ or â€œguns,â€ making it the most mentioned word in clips that talked about Oâ€™Rourke.4
Biden was still mentioned in more than twice as many cable news clips as Oâ€™Rourke in the two days after the debate, though. Unlike after the first debate, when Sen. Kamala Harris came very close to matching Bidenâ€™s share of media mentions, the data so far doesnâ€™t show that any other candidate substantially challenging Bidenâ€™s hegemony in cable news.
