Welcome to Pollapalooza, our weekly polling roundup.
â€œHow is the economy doing?â€ is a question that we have several hard, objective metrics with which to answer. But increasingly, how Americans think the economy is doing seems to depend on their party. But just because views of the economy are polarized, that doesnâ€™t mean theyâ€™re stagnant â€” and that could prove pivotal for President Trump in 2020.
Quinnipiac Universityâ€™s latest national poll of registered voters, conducted Aug. 21-26, found a huge gap between how Republicans and Democrats perceive the state of the economy: 43 percent of Republicans described it as â€œexcellent,â€ and another 45 percent described it as â€œgoodâ€; among Democrats, however, just 2 percent described the state of the economy as â€œexcellentâ€ and 37 percent said it was â€œgood.â€ A plurality of Democrats, 43 percent, thought it was â€œnot so good,â€ while 17 percent called it â€œpoor.â€
In total, 88 percent of Republicans used a positive adjective for the state of the economy, while only 39 percent of Democrats did the same. That 49-point gap in how the two parties perceived the strength of the economy was the second-largest that Quinnipiac has measured in the last three years.1 (The largest gap came this January, amid the government shutdown.)
Granted, itâ€™s not unusual for votersâ€™ politics to color their perceptions of the economy. During the Obama administration, Democrats were generally more optimistic about the economy than Republicans were; that flipped a few months into Trumpâ€™s tenure. Since then, Republicans have consistently viewed the economy more positively than Democrats have, but as the chart above shows, the gap between parties has really widened over time.
Most of this is due to Republicans warming to the economy, going from having a slight majority with positive views at the beginning of the Trump administration to near-universal approval today. Under the surface, Republicans havenâ€™t just gotten more likely to feel positively about the economy, theyâ€™ve also been reporting more strongly positive feelings. As late as April 2018, only 18 percent of Republicans said the state of the economy was â€œexcellentâ€ and 65 percent said it was â€œgood.â€ In May 2019, 50 percent rated it â€œexcellentâ€ and 42 percent rated it â€œgood.â€ That said, a bit of that enthusiasm did wear off in the latest poll, when the â€œexcellentâ€ number dropped by a few points. This could be the result of heightened anxiety that a recession might be around the corner.
But while Republicansâ€™ views on the economy have largely been on a steady march upward, Democratsâ€™ views appear to be more sensitive to events. In February 2018, after Trumpâ€™s first State of the Union address and a strong month in the stock market, 62 percent of Democrats had a positive view of the economy, but at moments like the January 2019 government shutdown or this most recent poll, positive views of the economy among Democrats have dipped to as low as 39 percent. But electorally, Republicansâ€™ and Democratsâ€™ views on the economy may not matter all that much; their 2020 votes are largely already set in stone.
So whatâ€™s perhaps more troubling for Trump is that independentsâ€™ opinions on the economy look a lot like Democratsâ€™ â€” they often react to current events in a similar way, though their recent baseline is about 20 points higher. While itâ€™s plausible that partisan polarization is so strong these days that even a recession would not change many votersâ€™ minds about Trump, the fact that independents appear persuadable on the economy is a point in favor of the theory that a recession would indeed damage his reelection chances.
Indeed, it might be a coincidence that Trumpâ€™s overall approval rating has ticked down in recent weeks amid speculation about a looming recession, but it also comes at a time when only 57 percent of independents have kind things to say about the state of the economy â€” the lowest number Quinnipiac has found since the summer of 2017.
According to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s presidential approval tracker, 41.4 percent of Americans approve of the job Trump is doing as president, while 53.9 percent disapprove (a net approval rating of -12.5 points). At this time last week, 41.3 percent approved and 54.2 percent disapproved (for a net approval rating of -12.9 points). One month ago, Trump had an approval rating of 42.4 percent and a disapproval rating of 53.2 percent, for a net approval rating of -10.8 points.
In our average of polls of the generic congressional ballot, Democrats currently lead by 6.5 percentage points (46.3 percent to 39.8 percent). A week ago, Democrats led Republicans by 6.7 points (46.4 percent to 39.7 percent). At this time last month, voters preferred Democrats by 6.1 points (46.1 percent to 40.0 percent).
