But even if the FEC deadlocks on investigations, even if itâ€™s unable to make affirmative rulings on whether someone broke the law â€” and this is often the case â€” at minimum these situations receive a full public airing. For instance, if special interest groups or others vehemently disagree with an FEC ruling, theyâ€™ll sue the organization.
Think of all the big court cases that have â€œFECâ€ in their names, with Citizens United v. FEC the biggest among them. Without a functioning FEC, this process grinds to a halt, for all intents and purposes.
clare.malone: Got it. So the shutdown is really affecting the transparency of the FEC.
nrakich: I find it interesting, though, that voters donâ€™t seem to care too much about campaign-finance violations. Thereâ€™s some research suggesting that they donâ€™t do as much as, say, sex scandals (probably for obvious reasons â€” theyâ€™re much drier!) to hurt candidates at the ballot box.
And I assume that most candidates will continue filing disclosure reports even if the FEC is shut down at the filing deadline. But what if they donâ€™t? Would they really suffer any consequences with voters? Iâ€™m not sure they would, and thatâ€™s scary to me.
clare.malone: I think thatâ€™s in part because itâ€™s so much a part of American political culture â€” and the culture at large â€” to see big money and politics as linked. Thereâ€™s a perception that thereâ€™s a degree of unfettered spending going on.
dave.levinthal: While the FEC doesnâ€™t have a quorum, if a political committee wanted to stop filing campaign-finance reports or otherwise violate campaign-finance rules, the FEC would not be in any position to do something about it.
Now, the FEC may very well pick up the matter once itâ€™s in business again. But for now, political committees donâ€™t really have anyone policing their activity in a way that would lead to some immediate penalty.
Said another way: The cops are at the station, theyâ€™re doing paperwork, but theyâ€™re not answering emergency calls.
sarahf: So given how critical the situation is, wonâ€™t one of Congressâ€™s first orders of business be appointing the one commissioner Trump has already nominated to get the FEC back up and running?
