It will be hard for Democrats to claw their way back to a majority in the Senate in 2020. Not only must they flip four currently Republican-held seats,1 but they must also prevent Republicans from picking up any seats of their own. And the GOP already has good shots at making gains in Alabama (thanks to the stateâ€™s deep Republican lean) and Michigan (thanks to a strong candidate).
Republicansâ€™ next-best pickup opportunity â€” at least according to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s partisan lean metric, which measures how much more Democratic- or Republican-leaning a place is than the country as a whole2 â€” is New Hampshire. And in recent weeks, a well-known Trump ally has signaled that heâ€™s interested in running: Corey Lewandowski, the original manager of President Trumpâ€™s 2016 campaign. This, however, is not a welcome development to many Republicans, who think Lewandowski would torpedo their chances of flipping the seat. But I donâ€™t think itâ€™s quite that cut-and-dried â€” those inside Trumpâ€™s and Lewandowskiâ€™s inner circles also have some valid arguments for why Lewandowski may be the right candidate for the job (more on that in a moment).
First, election handicappers are split on how vulnerable New Hampshireâ€™s Senate seat is. The Cook Political Report rates the race as â€œSolid Democraticâ€; Inside Elections thinks the race is a bit more competitive, rating it as â€œLikely Democraticâ€; and Sabatoâ€™s Crystal Ball puts it one step away from a toss-up at â€œLeans Democratic.â€ But the one thing they do agree on is that Democratic Sen. Jeanne Shaheen is currently favored. And Shaheen is a formidable incumbent: She was one of the few vulnerable Democratic senators to survive the 2014 Republican wave, defeating former Massachusetts Sen. Scott Brown by 3 percentage points. According to Morning Consult, she also has a +20 net approval rating3 despite residing in a slightly Republican-leaning state (according to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s partisan lean metric). That gives her one of the nationâ€™s best Popularity Above Replacement Senator scores, a measure of senatorsâ€™ cross-party appeal. As a result, I would expect her to run ahead of the Democratic presidential nominee in New Hampshire when both are on the ballot in 2020. In other words, Iâ€™d only expect her to be in danger if it looks like Trump will carry New Hampshire by a comfortable margin.
Three Republicans are already running against Shaheen, including retired Brigadier General Don Bolduc and former state House Speaker Bill Oâ€™Brien. But if Lewandowski runs, he could brush them aside easily in a Republican primary. Although he was fired as Trumpâ€™s campaign manager, Lewandowski is still close to the president. During a visit to New Hampshire this month, Trump told an interviewer, â€œCoreyâ€™s an outstanding guy. If he ran and won, he would be a great senator.â€ And if Lewandowski receives Trumpâ€™s formal endorsement, he would be a near lock for the nomination. When we analyzed Republican primaries in 2018, we found that candidates whom Trump endorsed won nearly all of their races; in fact, his endorsement was more correlated with primary victory than any other factor we examined.
But the general election might be a different story. Many Republicans, including Gov. Chris Sununu, worry that Lewandowskiâ€™s candidacy would go down like a lead balloon with the general electorate. Sununu is up for reelection in 2020 and is reportedly concerned that Lewandowski would drag down Republicans in other races. And the concern is not necessarily misplaced; Lewandowski does have plenty of flaws as a candidate. The Democratic PAC American Bridge has called him â€œan opposition researcherâ€™s dream candidate.â€ And according to The Washington Post, New Hampshire Democrats have already prepared a 25-page report on Lewandowskiâ€™s past career as a lobbyist. In 2016, Lewandowski was also charged with battery after forcefully grabbing a reporter who was trying to ask Trump a question. The charges were dropped, but video of the encounter may continue to haunt him. Not to mention, Lewandowski remains closely associated with Trump and shares his former bossâ€™s inflammatory style, both of which could backfire, as Trump is not particularly popular among Granite Staters. (Morning Consult gives Trump a -17 net approval rating in New Hampshire despite its light-red hue.)
On the other hand, one can make a case for Lewandowskiâ€™s electability as well. First, his national profile and connections to Trumpworld would ensure he is well-funded. Second, Iâ€™m not sure his association with Trump is a bad thing in a race where Republicans start out as underdogs. Establishment Republicansâ€™ criticism of Lewandowski boils down to, in Politicoâ€™s words, â€œhe would do little to help the party expand its base beyond the group of voters that Trump is already expected to attract.â€ But this is an odd critique in a Republican-leaning state that Trump may very well carry. In fact, all the major handicappers see the presidential race in New Hampshire as being more competitive than the Senate race, probably because Shaheenâ€™s aforementioned popularity makes her seat a safer bet for Democrats.4 If thatâ€™s true, then Republicans should want to nationalize the race, as their best chance of winning may be for every Trump voter to vote for a Republican Senate candidate as well. Given that he is essentially a down-ballot version of Trump, Lewandowski may be the best candidate to make sure GOP-leaning Granite Staters vote a straight ticket.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
If youâ€™ve been following our coverage of the Democratic primary, youâ€™ll know that I donâ€™t think much of media really understands Joe Bidenâ€™s popularity among Democrats. That doesnâ€™t mean that Biden is destined to win the primary. In fact, Iâ€™d regard him as an underdog relative to the field â€” that is, I think he has a less than 50 percent chance of getting the nomination â€” partly for reasons Iâ€™ll outline later on in this column. But there have already been several occasions when despite widespread predictions of Bidenâ€™s demise, the former vice president rebounded or held steady in the polls.
Furthermore â€” not totally unlike Donald Trump four years ago â€” Bidenâ€™s support comes mostly from the type of Democrats who are sometimes relatively invisible in media coverage of the campaigns, such as black Democrats and older Democrats without college degrees. Thatâ€™s another reason to be skeptical about claims that Biden isnâ€™t as popular as polls seem to imply. They sometimes reflect narratives that are filtered through journalistsâ€™ college-educated social environments â€” or conditioned by conversations on social media â€” with all the implicit biases those can introduce.
So this article about Biden in The New York Times, which alleged a disconnect between the polls and conditions on the ground In Iowa, was a little dismaying for me. Hereâ€™s a representative snippet:
But less than two weeks before Labor Day, when presidential campaigns traditionally kick into high gear, there are signs of a disconnect between his relatively rosy poll numbers and excitement for his campaign on the ground here [in Iowa], in the state that begins the presidential nominating process.
The thing is, I actually think the Times is onto something here! But itâ€™s something you can see in the polls. And itâ€™s something that probably has a lot to do with Iowa, where the article was datelined from â€” and where there are relatively few voters from among the groups that are most enthusiastic about Biden.
One straightforward way for a poll to detect voter enthusiasm is simply for it to ask voters how strongly they feel about a particular candidate. Many polls, for example, ask voters whether they have a very favorable, somewhat favorable, somewhat unfavorable or very unfavorable view of the candidates. If the Timesâ€™s hypothesis is correct about Biden, weâ€™d expect to see a lot of lukewarm support for him â€” plenty of voters in the â€œsomewhat favorableâ€ category, but relatively few in the â€œvery favorableâ€ bucket.
Thatâ€™s not really what national polls show, though. I averaged data from the four polls I can find that were conducted after the Detroit debate â€” from Morning Consult, YouGov, HarrisX and Fox News1 â€” that asked Democratic voters the four-pronged favorability question I described above. By this measure, Biden had just as much enthusiastic support as any other Democrat. In the polling average, 36 percent of Democrats had a very or strongly favorable view of Biden, essentially the same as for Bernie Sanders (37 percent) and Elizabeth Warren (36 percent) and well ahead of the next Democrat, Kamala Harris, at 26 percent.2
