Welcome to Political Confessional, a column about the views that Americans are scared to share with their friends and neighbors. In an increasingly polarized political climate, adherence to party or ideological orthodoxy seems de rigueur. Social media serves only to amplify that perception at times. 
But Americansâ€™ political views are often idiosyncratic and sometimes offensive, and they rarely adhere neatly to any particular party line. In this column, we want to dig into Americansâ€™ messy opinions on politics, morality and social mores. We hope that this exercise gives readers a glimpse into the minds of those with whom they might disagree â€” or agree! If you have a political belief that youâ€™re willing to share with us, fill out this form â€” we might get in touch.
This week we talked to Owen, a 37-year-old white man in California. He wrote that he is â€œopen to mass surveillance if it can lead to a world where a much higher percent of crimes are caught, leading to better public safety and, ideally, shorter [or] lighter sentences (because you donâ€™t need as big a threat of punishment to deter people from crimes if the likelihood of catching them is very high).â€
This interview has been edited and condensed for clarity.
Clare Malone: How did you come to this position?
Owen: I first started thinking about this after I heard a Radiolab episode that was about a period where, I think, Mexican cities were monitored by overhead drones that were taking a picture of the entire city maybe every 30 seconds. If a murder was committed, they could then go backwards in time and could say, â€œOK, hereâ€™s when we think the murder happened, hereâ€™s a car that showed up just before, hereâ€™s where that car went, hereâ€™s some other cars that recently committed some crimes and look, they all ended up in the same place. It looks like we found a gang.â€ And they were actually able to bust significant gangs through the ability to have a picture of the entire city every 30 seconds.
It just made the benefits of that type of surveillance very tangible, and it got me thinking, â€œWell, the benefits there are so obviously good, and if we could just get a lot of the stuff around law enforcement right â€” which is obviously an â€˜ifâ€™ â€” then the public benefits are so large.â€
It brings up all these other questions around racial justice [and] law enforcement: Are we actually policing the crimes we want to police? Is there still this rich-poor divide where rich, mostly white people get away with stuff and people of color do not? Those are all still open questions, but the idea that we would give up on this potential just because surveillance is icky â€¦ seems like thereâ€™s some baby being thrown out with the bathwater there.
All that said, in the wrong hands, surveillance is the tool of the oppressor. If you look at whatâ€™s going on in China, itâ€™s super scary, and itâ€™s enough to make me think, OK, maybe I should be backing off here, not dabbling in these waters.
CM: I want to drill down into what kind of mass surveillance youâ€™re thinking of. Are you thinking about a London-style system where you have video cameras everywhere? Should authorities be able to access your phone? How far do you think it should be able to go? 
Owen: What we think of as public space, I think itâ€™s OK if we have our eye on because in many public streets, we have security cameras in one place or another.
CM: What if your workplace, without you realizing it, has cameras? 
Owen: Thatâ€™s getting into the middle of the gradient where Iâ€™m not exactly sure. I think the workplace is maybe more public than private. I think Iâ€™m maybe more OK with visual surveillance than audio surveillance. People should be able to say what they want without thinking, â€œThe government is going to get me,â€ unless Iâ€™m talking seriously about committing violence. And then, how do you know Iâ€™m talking seriously about committing violence?
When it gets into private communications, I think maybe those should be totally private, but then youâ€™re allowing people to conspire.
CM: So you lean toward: â€œPeopleâ€™s private communications stay private?â€ 
Owen: Yes.
CM: What about the creepiness quotient? How do you answer to that? 
Owen: The creepiness factor is real. I think a lot of it comes down to: â€œDo you trust the creeper? Do you trust the person at the other end of the camera?â€ Government surveillance, when you donâ€™t trust the government, is uncomfortable.
CM: Do you trust the government? 
Owen: I am a comfortably middle-class white person and I havenâ€™t had many interactions where Iâ€™m like, â€œUh oh, this policeman might fuck me up right now,â€ whereas I have black friends where thatâ€™s something they have to think about all the time.
CM: You mentioned before that there were racial and social justice issues that come up. A lot of what youâ€™re talking about sounds like broken windows policing to me. How would you answer to that?
Owen: And thatâ€™s crossed my mind, and it makes me super uncomfortable. Who ends up getting policed when you do stuff like this? I like to think of it as something completely neutral, almost an algorithmic system where the robot watches all and just identifies crime, whoeverâ€™s doing it. But weâ€™ve seen all these examples where someone creates an AI [artificial intelligence system], and depending on what you expose the AI to, the AI becomes racist.
CM: Do you feel unsafe in your neighborhood or city?
Owen: Thatâ€™s not where it started, honestly. I generally feel pretty safe. Now I have a kid and another on the way. I think a little more about, â€œIs my kid going to be safe?â€ But I generally donâ€™t walk around too worried about it. But it feels like the potential is there to largely do away with gangs. There are some parts of the country where thatâ€™s a serious issue.
CM: Have you talked to anyone about this? 
Owen: Most of my friends are liberal. I think the general reaction is, â€œNo, you canâ€™t do that. The government surveilling everyone is clearly a bad idea.â€ I mentioned it to a black friend of mine and he said, â€œYeah, you do that, and the camera is going to be over the black neighborhood, and itâ€™s going to be the thing that makes it way easier to police black people for random shit.â€
