As my editors will tell you, I have a bad habit of leaving stories half-finished. Sometimes itâ€™s because I get bored or busy, but sometimes itâ€™s because the subject gets less and less newsworthy as Iâ€™m in the process of finishing a story.
Thatâ€™s the case with a story Iâ€™ve been working on about Beto Oâ€™Rourke, who has become less relevant to the Democratic primary now that heâ€™s polling at only about 3 percent. But the story may help to explain why Oâ€™Rourke has struggled so much, so Iâ€™m going to resurrect it in brief, bulletpoint form.
Hereâ€™s the gist of the argument: Oâ€™Rourke is probably competing for young voters more than for older ones, for white voters more than nonwhite ones, and for moderate voters more than for very liberal ones. (His voting record in Congress was fairly moderate, although the policy positions heâ€™s staking out now are more of a mixed bag.) There are plenty of young voters, white voters and moderate voters in the Democratic electorate. But there arenâ€™t that many who are young and white and moderate.
According to the Cooperative Congressional Election Study,1 63 percent of voters in the 2016 Democratic primaries were white, 51 percent identified themselves as moderate or conservative, and 56 percent were born in 1965 or afterward, per the Pew Research Center. Multiply those numbers together, and youâ€™d expect:
63% * 51% * 56% = ~18%
â€¦about 18 percent of Democrats to be all three things at once. Thatâ€™s enough to form a real base when youâ€™re competing for a party nomination, especially when Democratic rules require you to win at least 15 percent of voters in a state or congressional district to secure convention delegates.
But when you actually look at individual-level voter data, you find something different: Only 12 percent of Democratic primary voters are young and white and moderate. Thatâ€™s far fewer voters to go around, especially when youâ€™re also competing with, say, Pete Buttigieg for the same voters.
What gives? Well, these various characteristics are correlated with one another, so you canâ€™t just multiply the different numbers together to come up with the right number of voters, which would imply that they were independent from one another. And theyâ€™re correlated in ways that are not helpful for Beto (or Buttigieg). Younger Democrats tend to be more liberal than older ones. And white voters â€” not all whites, but the ones who vote in Democratic primaries â€” are more liberal than minorities. There are some young, white, moderate Democrats, but not as many as youâ€™d expect.
Share of 2016 Democratic primary and caucus voters, grouped by age, race and ideology
Source: Cooperative Congressional Election StUDY
Conversely, there are more young, white, liberal voters (i.e. the Bernie Sanders base) than youâ€™d expect in the electorate than if these characteristics were uncorrelated, and also more old, white, moderate voters than youâ€™d expect (i.e. Joe Biden base). These are the â€œhot spotsâ€ in the electorate, so to speak. After that, the next-largest groups in the electorate are old, white liberals (probably a good group for Elizabeth Warren) and young, relatively moderate nonwhite voters (which could be a good one for Kamala Harris, especially if she tacks more to the center).
That doesnâ€™t explain or excuse all of Oâ€™Rourkeâ€™s problems. But he has less of a natural base of voters than many of the leading candidates do, which doesnâ€™t only hurt his standing in the polls but also means there are fewer people willing to stand up to defend him when things are going poorly, as they have been recently.\n|end|\n
