Was 2020 the end of the Iowa caucuses as we know them? After Monday nightâ€™s debacle â€” in which fewer than 2 percent of Iowa caucus sites reported results as an apparent consequence of technical difficulties and â€œinconsistenciesâ€ in the results â€” many commentators (including us) asked just that. Even Iowans are starting to wonder whether the caucuses are the best way for their voices to be heard.
Brian Vogel, a supporter of Sen. Elizabeth Warren who was among the few who stayed until the very end of the caucus at Iowa Cityâ€™s Precinct 21, said the caucuses felt like a relic of a past era, when a few dozen neighbors would gather in a living room to hash out which candidate to support. â€œThere was a lot of bickering and talk of policy and lobbying back and forth,â€ he said. But that didnâ€™t really happen at his precinct. Only a handful of the 800 caucusgoers there eventually switched sides, and many people left after the first round of voting. â€œIt feels like weâ€™re at a point where itâ€™s more logical for us to cast a ballot,â€ Vogel said. â€œIf all of us were to just walk through the door and make marks for our preference and leave, the results would have been basically the same.â€
Thereâ€™s evidence that many Iowans actually prefer a change. A September 2019 poll, conducted by Selzer and Co. for the Des Moines Register/CNN/Mediacom, found that likely Democratic caucusgoers in Iowa were split on switching to a primary. Forty-four percent said that it was more important for Iowa to hold a primary â€œso everyone can vote, even if it means Iowa would no longerâ€ vote first, while 42 percent said it was better for Iowa to go first â€œeven if it means not everyone who wants to can participate on caucus night.â€
Indeed, switching to a primary probably would mean Iowa would no longer be the first state to vote in presidential nominating processes. Thatâ€™s because New Hampshire has a stranglehold on holding the first primary in the nation; there is even a state law that the New Hampshire secretary of state pick a primary election date that is at least seven days before any â€œsimilar election.â€ Iowaâ€™s party elders might be unhappy about their stateâ€™s loss of influence over the primary process, but rank-and-file Iowans might not actually care that much about voting a little later in the process.
And after the bad headlines generated Monday night, it would hardly be surprising if scrapping the caucuses becomes even more popular. Some caucusgoers seemed pretty comfortable with the idea that Iowa might exchange its first-in-the-nation status for a process that was less time-consuming and more flexible. â€œItâ€™s a point of pride, but Iâ€™m not sure if itâ€™s appropriate for Iowa to caucus first anyway,â€ Matt Bailey, a Cedar Rapids resident who caucused for former South Bend, Indiana, Mayor Pete Buttigieg, said before the chaos unfolded Monday night. â€œI think most people here understand that itâ€™s not the right setup anymore â€” in terms of the complicated and time-consuming nature of the caucus itself, and the fact that we go first.â€
Even before Monday, the caucuses were already under fire for being undemocratic: Many people cannot afford to take a few hours off in the evening to go caucus; they present accessibility challenges to people with disabilities; until this year, there was no option to vote absentee (and this yearâ€™s option was still pretty flawed); and there is no option to vote a secret ballot. At a campaign event over the weekend, a couple named Jeff and Melissa1 explained that only one of them would be caucusing Monday night because Jeff, who has a shift job, couldnâ€™t get out of work. Melissa, meanwhile, said she would be caucusing with their 1-year-old baby strapped into his carrier. â€œItâ€™s really not ideal, because itâ€™s way past his bedtime, but I donâ€™t have another option if I want to caucus,â€ she said.
The Iowa Democratic Party did take some steps this year to make the process more open by adding a handful of satellite caucus locations at places like assisted living facilities and hospitals, or scheduling them earlier in the day. About two dozen people showed up to caucus at the Cedar Rapids Public Library on Monday afternoon, and many of them seemed relieved to have an option that didnâ€™t involve hanging out in a crowded room for several hours that evening. â€œI was really upset because I have to work this evening and didnâ€™t think I was going to be able to caucus,â€ said Jill Martinez, a longtime caucusgoer. She said the satellite caucus felt very different than an ordinary caucus â€” smaller, and more informal â€” but that wasnâ€™t a problem. â€œHonestly, Iâ€™m glad to have skipped the crowds.â€
There are other reasons, too, why Iowans might appreciate a switch to a primary. Lisa Lower, who attended the Cedar Rapids satellite caucus, said midday Monday she didnâ€™t caucus back in 2016 because she was leaning toward Sen. Bernie Sanders but didnâ€™t want her Hillary Clinton-supporting friends and neighbors to know. â€œI hate caucuses,â€ Lower said. â€œVoting is a very, very personal activity. I just am not comfortable basically being naked in front of my neighbors, saying, â€˜This is who Iâ€™m voting for.â€™ Thatâ€™s why we should just have a primary like everyone else.â€
Of course, there are still Iowans who see the caucuses as an important vestige of a truly democratic process, and they will likely fight to keep them. â€œIn Iowa, a caucus is about consensus-building with your neighbors and itâ€™s participatory,â€ said Dave Tingwald, a precinct chair in Iowa City, as he and other volunteers waited Monday night to phone in their results. â€œI think itâ€™s incredibly healthy for democracy. It gives ordinary people access to their government.â€
And ultimately, the decision whether to scrap the caucuses in the next presidential race will be made not by ordinary caucusgoers, but by party elites â€” which means it may not even matter if a majority of Iowa voters support a switch. Frustrations seem likely to continue to build, but Iowans still might find themselves back in a high school gymnasium in four years, waiting for the next caucuses to begin.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
More than 14 hours after the Iowa caucuses began, we still donâ€™t have any official results, and itâ€™s becoming clear that an app is at least partly to blame.
An app designed to let caucus leaders report results seems to have had problems including user error, lack of connectivity and an insufficient backup plan, demonstrating exactly why itâ€™s so difficult â€” and risky â€” to introduce new technology into elections.
â€œRight now, a lot of the election security community is trying to, as nicely as possible, say â€˜We told you so,â€™â€ said Maggie MacAlpine, a co-founder of Nordic Innovation Labs, a firm of security consultants whose specialties include safeguarding elections.
This year, the Iowa Democratic Party, which runs the stateâ€™s Democratic caucuses, introduced a smartphone app that local precinct chairs could use to send in tallies from their caucus sites. Immediately, election security experts raised concerns because the party wouldnâ€™t reveal who built the app, what testing had been done, or who they had consulted to make sure it was secure.
The party insisted, however, that thorough security measures had been put in place, and besides, precinct chairs could always fall back on the reporting technology theyâ€™ve been using for decades: a phone-in hotline. One problem: Multiple precinct chairs reported hours-long wait times, and even getting cut off, when they tried to use that hotline.
Even before the caucuses began, some precinct chairs reported difficulty with the app, including trouble downloading it. Additionally, one county chairman told The New York Times that seven of the 10 volunteers running precincts in his district never downloaded the app at all and always planned to call in the results.
These problems demonstrate one of the first big mistakes the party made when introducing new tech to an already arcane process: not considering its user base.
â€œOne of the reasons election security is such a difficult problem to solve is because the people who are operating elections arenâ€™t tech people,â€ MacAlpine said. â€œTheyâ€™re often retirees, people who are trying to help their community.â€
Compounding the issue, many of these events also take place in rural areas where cell phone reception is less reliable. In that way, even if the app functioned perfectly, it already failed on a practical level if the people who were intended to use it didnâ€™t understand it or couldnâ€™t access it.
But, according to the Iowa Democratic Party, the app didnâ€™t work perfectly, either.
â€œWhile the app was recording data accurately, it was reporting out only partial data,â€ Troy Price, chair of the Iowa Democratic Party, said in a statement released Tuesday morning, adding that the error was due to a coding issue that was later fixed.
Though the party still isnâ€™t revealing many details about how the app was tested beforehand, a bug like this suggests it was not adequately tested at scale in the way it would be used on caucus night.
â€œThere are some really good things to do when youâ€™re rolling out any kind of tech in any high-stakes situation,â€ said Dana Chisnell, an expert on design in elections and former co-director at the Center for Civic Design. â€œYou would want to do a lot of testing in lots of different ways, from reliability and resilience to usability and access. The evidence suggests those kinds of tests were not done.â€
Both Chisnell and MacAlpine questioned why the party didnâ€™t simply use the caucuses as a chance to pilot an app, rather than diving into a full roll out. But in a way, the party already piloted using an app back in 2016. Both the Republican and Democratic parties in Iowa introduced apps built by Microsoft to report results during the caucuses in 2016. And it didnâ€™t work last time, either, with multiple results not properly transmitted.
The good news, if there is any, is that because the Iowa caucuses also have a robust paper trail and donâ€™t require a secret ballot, it should be possible to verify the results in spite of the massive collapse of the reporting system, and the Iowa Democratic Party chairman said in his statement thatâ€™s exactly what the party is doing now. But the fallout from the disastrous results-night-that-wasnâ€™t threatens the future of the caucuses themselves â€” and maybe even impacted this yearâ€™s nomination process.\n|end|\n
\n|begin|\n
In trying to build a forecast model of the Democratic primaries, we literally had to think about the entire process from start (Iowa) to finish (the Virgin Islands on June 6). Actually, we had to do more than that. Since the nomination process is sequential â€” states vote one at a time rather than all at once â€” we had to determine, empirically, how much the results of one state can affect the rest.
The answer in the case of Iowa is that it matters a lot. Despite its demographic non-representativeness, and the quirks of the caucuses process, the amount of media coverage the state gets makes it far more valuable a prize than youâ€™d assume from the fact that it only accounts for 41 of the Democratsâ€™ 3,979 pledged delegates.
More specifically, we estimate â€” based on testing how much the results in various states have historically changed the candidatesâ€™ position in national polls â€” that Iowa was the second most-important date on the calendar this year, trailing only Super Tuesday. It was worth the equivalent of almost 800 delegates, about 20 times its actual number.
Expected bounce magnitude according to FiveThirtyEightâ€™s primary model
Everything was a little weird in Iowa this year, however. And there were already some signs that the Iowa bounce â€” which essentially results from all the favorable media coverage that winning candidates get â€” might be smaller than normal. Iowa was bracketed by an extremely busy news calendar: President Trumpâ€™s impeachment trial both before and after the caucuses, the Super Bowl on Sunday, the State of the Union address on Tuesday. There was not the usual climactic uptick in media coverage around Iowa. From initial indications â€” to the extent any information at all is reliable at this point â€” Democratic turnout there wound up being fairly low.
But we werenâ€™t prepared for what actually happened, which is that â€” as Iâ€™m writing this at 3:15 a.m. on Tuesday â€” the Iowa Democratic Party literally hasnâ€™t released any results from its caucuses. Iâ€™m not going to predict what those numbers will eventually be, although early indications are that Bernie Sanders, Pete Buttigieg and perhaps Elizabeth Warren had good results. The point is that the lead story around the 2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses is now â€” and will forever be â€” the colossal shitshow around the failure to release results in a timely fashion.
Maybe there will eventually be a decent-sized Iowa bounce despite all of this. But thereâ€™s a good chance that the candidates who did well in Iowa get screwed, and the candidates who did poorly there get a mulligan. To repeat: Thereâ€™s very little importance in a mathematical sense to who wins 41 delegates. Iowa is all about the media narrative it produces and all about momentum, and that momentum, whoever wins, is likely to have been blunted.
Who might this help? Letâ€™s pretend for a moment we donâ€™t have any hints about how the results might have turned out. In fact, letâ€™s pretend that Iowa didnâ€™t happen at all. I reran our forecast model as though the Iowa caucuses were canceled.1 Hereâ€™s how that changed each candidateâ€™s chances of getting a delegate majority:
Chances of winning a majority of pledged delegates per FiveThirtyEight forecast model on Feb. 3 (pre-Iowa), compared with a version of the model that skips the Iowa caucuses
The presence of Iowa was helpful to Sanders, whose chances of winning a national delegate majority would have been 24 percent without Iowa â€” as compared to the 31 percent chance that he had with Iowa, as of Monday afternoon. Iowa hurt Biden, however, whose chances of a delegate majority would have been 50 percent without it, rather than 43 percent with it.
And Iowa was extremely helpful to Buttigieg, whose chances of winning the delegate majority were fairly low even with Iowa â€” keep in mind that he had slipped to third in polls of Iowa and fifth in national polls â€” but would have been virtually nonexistent (less than 1 percent) without it.
By giving the winning candidates a boost, the presence of Iowa also reduced the chance of an unstructured race and a potential brokered convention. The chance of there being no delegate majority was 17 percent without Iowa, but would have been 20 percent with it.
Granted, none of those changes â€” say, 24 percent versus 31 percent â€” are necessarily that large. But thatâ€™s partly because, as of Monday afternoon, four or five candidates appeared to have a shot at winning Iowa. For the candidate who actually won Iowa, it would have been a much bigger deal. We estimate that Sandersâ€™s chances of a majority would have shot up to from 31 percent to 58 percent with an Iowa win, Warrenâ€™s from 5 percent to 32 percent, and Buttigiegâ€™s from 4 percent to 22 percent.
And in some ways that still discounts Iowaâ€™s impact, because several of the campaigns â€” for better or worse â€” built their entire strategy around the state. Would Buttigieg have been a major player in the race without Iowa? Considering his lack of support among black voters, probably not. Would candidates such as Kamala Harris, Cory Booker and Julian Castro have dropped out so soon? Thatâ€™s a harder call, since Harris, Booker and Castro werenâ€™t polling particularly well anywhere. But the Democratic field might have remained a little more diverse.
So weâ€™ve arrived at a point of some ambivalence. On the one hand, candidates such as Buttigieg, who seemingly did well there, are liable to be injured by the muddled storylines in Iowa following the results-reporting disaster on Monday night. On the other hand, itâ€™s not clear why Iowa was afforded so much importance in the first place, and Buttigieg possibly owed his entire presence in the campaign to this quirk in the nomination process. Nonetheless, these were the rules of the game as every candidate understood them. So if Iowa turns out not to matter very much because of the results-reporting snafu, they have every right to be upset.
To be even more blunt: The Iowa Democratic Partyâ€™s colossal screw-up in reporting results will potentially have direct effects on the outcome of the nomination process. The failure to report results will almost certainly help Biden, assuming that indications that he performed poorly in Iowa are correct, as they wonâ€™t get nearly as much media coverage. And theyâ€™ll hurt whichever candidate wins the state â€” most likely Sanders or Buttigieg. (Although if Sanders winds up finishing in second place or lower, he also might not mind a reduction in the importance of Iowa, especially with one of his best states, New Hampshire, coming up next.)
Furthermore, Iowa is typically a state that winnows the field. But with every candidate either having performed well there, potentially having an excuse for a disappointing finish there, or somewhere in between, it might not do that. Delaying the winnowing process would tangibly increase the chance of a contested convention.
Itâ€™s not a good situation for the Democratic Party. And itâ€™s already too late for the damage to be entirely undone, even if Iowa eventually gets its act together.
