Two months ago, we set out to track how Americans are responding to President Trumpâ€™s impeachment in real time. And what weâ€™ve found in our polling with Ipsos, where we interview the same group of respondents every few weeks using Ipsosâ€™s KnowledgePanel, is that while a majority of Americans do think Trump committed an impeachable offense, not many are changing their minds on impeachment. The partisan splits on the impeachment process run deep, and, if anything, the public is only becoming more divided.
But those top line results, while helpful for understanding the political stakes for the senators who will soon be voting on whether to acquit or convict the president, donâ€™t necessarily tell us much about how Americans are feeling about impeachment. So to try to capture some of the emotions churning beneath the surface, we asked our respondents whether they thought the impeachment process was a good or bad use of Congressâ€™s time and had them give us a few words they would use to describe the impeachment process.
Share of respondents in a FiveThirtyEight/Ipsos poll who said they thought the impeachment process is a bad use of Congressâ€™s time, by party
From a poll with 1,587 respondents, conducted Jan. 17-20, 2020.
Many Americans donâ€™t think Congress should be spending its time on impeachment, but there is a pretty big split between Democrats and Republicans on this question. Overall, a slight majority (51 percent) of Americans say the process is a bad use of Congressâ€™s time, while 45 percent say itâ€™s a good use of time. But only 25 percent of Democrats say the process has been a bad use of time, compared with 85 percent of Republicans who say the same.
Among those who said impeachment was a bad use of time, a plurality (39 percent) said that itâ€™s because the process distracts Congress from more important issues. Another 33 percent said itâ€™s because Trump didnâ€™t commit an impeachable offense. For those who thought impeachment has been a good use of Congressâ€™s time, a majority (55 percent) said itâ€™s because itâ€™s Congressâ€™s job to investigate potential wrongdoing by the president.1
Why respondents in a FiveThirtyEight/Ipsos poll said the impeachment process is a good or bad use of Congressâ€™s time
From a poll with 1,587 respondents, conducted Jan. 17-20, 2020.
We also asked respondents an open-ended question that allowed them to share a few words for how theyâ€™d describe the impeachment process. In the most recent wave of our survey, 24 percent of Republicans mentioned â€œwasteâ€ in their description of the impeachment process, a notable increase over the last two waves, when around 17 percent of GOP respondents used the word. The words mentioned by Democrats, meanwhile, have been all over the map, with â€œnecessaryâ€ and â€œTrumpâ€ showing up the most â€” but not nearly as frequently as â€œwasteâ€ did among Republicans.
Share of respondents, by party, who used a given word in response to an open-ended question about how theyâ€™d describe the impeachment process, in a FiveThirtyEight/Ipsos poll
From a poll conducted Jan. 17-20, 2020, with 1,587 respondents.
It is likely not a coincidence that â€œwaste of timeâ€ is a phrase that Trump and his allies frequently use to describe the impeachment process. The news coverage of the impeachment process may also be driving some of what we see in our data. For example, respondents in our survey who said they mostly watched Fox News were much likelier than those who got their news from other sources to describe impeachment as a â€œwaste.â€ â€œSham,â€ â€œwitch huntâ€ and â€œstupidâ€ â€” all fixtures of Trumpâ€™s impeachment vocabulary â€” appeared with some regularity in Republicansâ€™ responses to the question.
Itâ€™s hard, of course, to know whether the growing perception among Republicans that impeachment is a â€œwasteâ€ is connected to some of the other trends weâ€™ve seen in our polling with Ipsos, including the fact that Republicansâ€™ support for Trump has grown, along with their skepticism about key elements of the Democratsâ€™ case against the president. But together, these trends indicate that over the past few months, at least some additional Republicans have fallen into line behind Trump. In fact, and as the chart below shows, Republicans are increasingly likely to use similar words to describe the impeachment process as compared to Democrats, who remain much less cohesive.
Democratsâ€™ most common responses are also noteworthy for what they didnâ€™t include. Words linked to the substance of the charges against Trump, like â€œUkraineâ€ or â€œquid pro quo,â€ werenâ€™t among those that were most frequently mentioned by Democrats. Instead, common descriptions hinged on the length of the process (â€œlongâ€ and â€œslowâ€), the figure at the center of the drama (â€œTrumpâ€ and â€œpresidentâ€), or the reasons for its existence (â€œnecessaryâ€ and â€œjusticeâ€). And about 5 percent of Democrats also used the word â€œwasteâ€ to describe impeachment, perhaps reflecting the not-insignificant number who think the process has been a bad use of Congressâ€™s time.
Polls can only tell us so much, of course, about how people are feeling â€” even when respondents are allowed to describe their perspective in their own words. But these findings do give us a window into how people on both sides of the impeachment debate are absorbing the process â€” and how they might continue to think about it after the final Senate vote is tallied. If nothing else, the fact that â€œwaste,â€ â€œTrumpâ€ and â€œpartisanâ€ are the only words that were frequently used by both Republicans and Democrats paints a fairly bleak picture of where Americans can find common ground when it comes to impeachment.\n|end|\n
